Chaos has broken out at a fundraiser in Muhoroni constituency in a clash between supporters of MP Onyango Koyoo (NDM) and those of Kisumu county assembly majority leader Samuel Ongow (ODM). The youths allied to Ongow resisted their advance, prompting the clash. They drew out machetes against each other. Ten injuries.
A man is lynched for allegedly killing his brother.

A middle-aged man has been lynched at Shibale village. Residents said the man was behind a gang that robbed a cybercafe in Mumias town. The mob caught up with him in the town and frogmarched to River Nzoia Bridge, where he was stoned him to death and his body set ablaze.

St Josephs Kocholia Secondary School in Busia county was closed indefinitely. Education officials in Teso North ordered the closure of the institution after the more than 500 students boycotted classes. The students marched to the district education offices in Amagoro to seek audience with area education boss Genetrix Amatha. The students demanded the resignation of the schools Board of Management chairman Dudovicus Okitoi. They accused Okitoi of being behind the high turnover of principals at the institution.

A group of youths stormed the Olkaria geothermal plant in Naivasha to demand for jobs. Armed with crude weapons, the irate youths paralysed operations at the Green Energy Station involved in the construction of wellhead generators. Though armed, it is not clear if the protesters used their weapons in violent manner.
Suspected Liyu militia assassinate a ONLF sympathiser along Kismayo Road in Garissa.
A 42-year-old man was burnt to death by a vigilante mob at Imbisi village in Mumias district for killing his daughter.
A mob lynches a man in Kilgoris for suspected rape.

A man is lynched in Molo, Nakuru county. He is suspected to be part of a gang that has been abducting, raping and killing girls in the area. The residents attacked the man on the banks of River Moto, barely two days after the body of a girl was discovered in the river.

Meru University students rioted to protest a poor health unit, water shortage and security. The rampage lasted less than 30 minutes, but two vehicles were burnt, car windows were smashed and vehicles overturned.
At least 21 people have been killed in new attacks late in the day in Kenyas Lamu coastal region. Al Shabaab claimed responsibility.
Boda boda operators on lynched two suspected robbers at Gatura village in Gatanga subcounty.
At least 12 people were killed when attackers managed to get a suspected ringleader of Mpeketoni attacks out of a police station in Kenyas Tana Delta County.

Thousands of protesters demonstrated in Mpeketoni over insecurity . They carried placards and twigs as they appealed to the government to curb runaway crime. They condemned the recent killings in the county and asked for speedy investigations .
Police in Kisumu use tear gas to disperse protesters along the streets who were marching in support of Saba Saba day anniversary.

Police fired tear gas in central Nairobi to disperse a crowd of several hundred anti-government demonstrators in the streets. The demonstrators are opposed to President Uhuru Kenyatta and carried posters of opposition leader Raila Odinga, chanting "Uhuru must go." No reported violence.

A group of 30 to 50 armed men, believed to be attached to the recent attacks in Hindi, attack Gamba police station (Ndeu area) during the evening hours. The attackers overpowered the security officers the torched the station. One officer reported dead, two others injured. Shabelle Media Network reports nine officers dead.

At least one person was killed and several injured late in the day in the grenade blast in a restaurant in Kenyas north-eastern town of Wajir, before spraying the building with bullets and escaping. No one claimed immediate responsibility for the killing.
Students from Khabukoshe Mixed Secondary School in Matungu embark on a protest against the school head, accusing the headmaster of mismanagement.
Residents of Bomet County protest poor road construction in Cheboingong location.
Unidentified assailants attack Pandanguo location, no immediate reports of causalities.
Unidentified persons shoot and killed a prominent businessman near the airport. Though the killers remain unknown the source alludes to al Shabaab, as they have been active in the area lately.
Residents protest poor roads in Kisumu. The exact date of the protest is not known.

Fresh attacks have been reported in Ras Kitua area in Lamu. Reports say gunmen raided villages in Manda Island, stole household goods and torched several houses before disappearing into Boni forest. Lamu County Commissioner Miiri Njenga says they are conducting aerial patrols to hunt down the attackers. Causalities not listed. The attack may have had occurred on 14/07.
Muslim students "violently" protest after they are barred from their school after converting a Christian student to Islam. The extent of the violence is not known.

Residents of Ngumu village in Tanadelta sub county protest against harassment by police in the ongoing operation to root out street gangs that have been killing people in the past month. The residents allege the police force witnesses to publically point out gang members, which causes them to fear attacks from the gang.
In response to recent attacks in the Lamu area, Kenya air forces launch attacks on Lamu Forest, believed to be where the suspected assailants are hiding. Causalities not known.
Demonstrators embark on a "peace walk" from Kilifi to Kwale County to protest against recent insecurity in the area.
Demonstrators embark on a "peace walk" from Kilifi to Kwale County (specific locations within Kwale not known) to protest against recent insecurity in the area.
Police officer candidates protest unfair hiring practices by the police forces.
Residents protest the death of a woman who they allege died in police custody.
Residents in Nyeri town demonstrated against poor road conditions. They said the road leading to the Nyeri Provincial General Hospital is filled with potholes.

Hundreds of Nakuru residents stormed a police station in the town and set free petty crime offenders after they accused police of being involved in the death of a woman while in custody. Two officers were injured during the protests and have been hospitalized. It is not clear if this event has any relation to a similar protest in Kiptagich.

Operations at a Kitui West police outpost were temporarily disrupted after members of public stormed the premises demanding speedy investigations into the killing of a villager. The exact date of the protest is not known.
Unidentified gunmen attack a Mombasa-bound bus outside of Witu, kill seven, including police officers. The following morning al Shabaab claimed responsibility for the attack.

Six Turkana herders have been killed during the afternoon hours following an attack by Pokot raiders on a village in Kaakong area in Kainuk location, Turkana county. Three women are among seven other people injured in the ongoing attack by cattle rustlers from the neighbouring Pokot region. There has been repeated conflict along the Pokot - Turkana border as competition for resources and cattle rustling take centre stage.
Students of Karaba Secondary School in Mbeere South sub county riot over a lack of eggs available in the area. One injury and property damage reported.

Three are killed (some sources claim four) and several other injured in an al Shabaab-linked shooting (later discover to be ODM) in the Likoni area in Mombasa. It was learned the shooting was retribution for an earlier raid on an al Shabaab location.

Hooded gunmen killed two people at a bar in the Majengo area of Mombasa Monday night (July 21st) after they entered and began shooting randomly. Authorities believe a connection between this attack and the one in Likoni may be connected.
Residents of Kitengela forced a local factory to close after staging a protest against "foul smells and dust" caused by the factory.
At least 50 boda boda operators barricaded an earth road in Kericho town to protest its poor state.
Machakos Pivot Institute of Community Development & Social Work college students protest a university student fee mishap.
Two robbery suspects were attacked by a mob at Oyugis. One killed, the second critically injured.
Residents hold a demonstrations against their districts police hiring practices.

A German tourist is killed and a Ugandan tourist is injured after their attackers assaulted them along Kuze Road in the Old Town area. Nothing appeared to be stolen from the two. The source makes mention of al Shabaab activity in the area, but makes no assumptions as to the responsible party.
Police shoot two suspected al Shabaab members dead as they foil a planned attack on the city.
Police shoot two al Shabaab suspects who were attempting to place bombs on a ship docked at the citys port.
Two are shot and killed in Garba Gola by unidentified gunmen. The reason for the killing is not known, but it should be noted one of the victims was Somali.
Student at a secondary school riot, demanding improved school provided meals.
About 100 temporary health workers in Baringo county protest in Kabarnet for permanent placement.

Kenyans on held peaceful demonstrations outside Kakuma refugee camp in northwest Kenya over the sacking of pregnant female employees from an international aid agency. Hundreds of local residents matched outside the UNHCR compound, demanding the reinstatement of the three employees allegedly sacked by the Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC) after they became pregnant.
Leaders of African Inland Church in the Tudor area of Mombasa protested the sale of their land to private investors in a process they termed as illegal.

The Kenyan police arrested an official of al Shabaab in Nairobi on 06/08. The suspect, a journalist by profession (Andulus Radio), is accused of killing journalists in Somalia. However, the man under interrogation has denied that he is Mr Hanafi. SNG requested the Kenyan government to extradite him to Mogadishu to face charges there. Somalia ambassador to Kenya Mohamed Ali Nur has said his government has appealed to the government of Kenya to extradite al Shabaab Al Andulus radio director back to Somalia for prosecution process. According to the ambassador, the arrest of the key official comes as the result of cooperation between NISA and their Kenyan counterpart.
Residents of Khwisero village in Kakamega county have lynched a man accused of killing his father.

Gunmen hurled explosives at the Mandera county government headquarters causing damages. The buildings wing that houses finance and other executive offices was destroyed in the attack. Perpetrators believed to be al Shabaab. No injuries reported.
More than 30 villagers protested the arrest of a resident in Barwesa division, Baringo North sub county who was arrested recently for poaching. The protesters maintained his innocence.
Residents protest at a police station for the release of suspected elephant poacher, whos innocence theyve maintained.

More than 600 boda boda operators protested against harassment by traffic police officers. The protest began at 7am after an operator was pushed off his motorcycle by two officers in a tinted Probox car and got hurt. Governor James Ongwae was caught up in the protest, with the operators refusing to let him pass until he addressed their grievances.

Miraa dealers in Embu blocked the Embu-Kiritiri road at Muraru and Gachoka areas protesting high levies imposed by the county government. They used stones and burned tyres. Police dispersed the protesters.

Two police officers were injured during the evening hours injured after al Shabaab gunmen attacked a police station in Mandera. The gang of about 100 is said to have attacked at the Fino Police station in the night using rifles.
M-Pesa agents protest increasing levels of area violence following the killing of two traders by robbers in Kibuye market.
A 27-year -old man has been lynched in Irunduni village, Tharaka, after he and two others raided a home and attempted to kidnap the wife of a prominent businessman.
Two casual laborious were shot dead by unknown assailants, later suspected to al Shabaab in the outskirts of Garissa town on the evening of 13/08.
Suspected al Shabaab, numbering 5, killed a road construction worker in Mandera County before fleeing across the border into Somalia.
Hundreds of women and youths protested against a illegal abortion providing medic on Bungoma town streets.
Suspected al Shabaab shot and killed a quarry worker before fleeing into Somalia. Authorities speculate the motive for the attack is related to the presence of Kenya troops in Somalia.
Residents of Kimangaru village, Embu West sub county protest the poor state of the Kimangaru-Embu road. They dug a trench across a road blocking motorists from accessing the towns.

More than 500 employees of Bungoma County at the weekend (precise date not known) camped at the county headquarters in Bungoma town to protest against perceived favouritism in a employee selection process.
Al-Shabaab fighters have reportedly kidnapped 22 people from North-eastern Kenyan district of Mandera. The perpetrators later released the group after taking their possessions.

Suspected al Shabaab attack a police post in Bothai around the midnight hour between Monday and Tuesday. The ensuing gun battle lasted five hours, eventually causing the police forces to abandon their post. After the police fled the gunmen ransacked the village, stealing drugs. Deaths reported, though no hard numbers were provided.
Al Shabaab attacks and kills two, steals vehicles at Basuba location, Lamu East. Security forces later launched a security sweep of the area.

A khat driver is kidnapped by al Shabaab while three of his colleagues were attacked, robbed and released as they travelled in or near Bothai, possibly Kiunga. It was later learned the driver was beheaded sometime later.
Residents protest the poor state of a road.
Residents protest the poor state of a road.

A Star reporter is attacked and injured by angry Maasais, who were destroying the Hazardous Waste Company. The reporter was attacked while taking photos for his assignment of a burning factory. The Maasai group had assembled at the factory for a meeting that lasted two hours before they decided to set the plant on fire. Two others were injured by the mob.
A group protest a Jubilee Government "pyramid scheme" which caused many financial ruin.
Samburu and Borana herders clash over a water source. Four killed, two each side.
A vigilante mob kills a suspected thief and injures his accomplice in Sega town.
Colleagues of a man beheaded by al Shabaab in Bothai protest in Maua, demanding the arrest of the perpetrators.
Twenty dead (range as high as 30) and 300 displaced as a result of a seven-hour ethnically driven gun battle in Rhamu. Police have made at least one arrest and recovered various light arms.
A clash between Garre and Degodia clans continue into a second day. Two additional combatants killed. The Garre may have been from Ethiopia, who came later to reinforce the Kenyan Garre.
Unidentified gunmen attack an ambulance near Mandera (Isaack Kora town), injuring the driver. The attack may be in relation to a nearby clash between Garre and Degodia clans.
A group of 200 Boda Boda operators gather at Kabarnet stadium to protest against heavy handiness from police.
Six are reported injured following a explosion near a hospital in Mandera. Perpatrators unknown, though the attack may be related to a nearby ethnic clash between Garre and Degodia clans.

Four al Shabaab-linked gunmen shoot and kill a senior police officer in the Tudor area of Mombasa. Some accounts claim the attack occurred in Old Town, which is a short distance south. Apparently two of the gunmen were foreign, German and Russian.

Eight people are feared dead after about 200 heavily armed Garre militia from Ethiopia carried out an attack on the Degodia-dominated town. The attackers, who were dressed in military fatigues raided Banisa in Guba Sub-Location and targeted shops, villages, a school and a dispensary. The two clans have been recently been clashing in the area.
Demonstrators destroy a waste plant and injured a journalist while protesting against the plants emissions, which they believe are hazardous to their health.
Residents stone two suspected robbers to death.
Residents protest against the principal of a school whom they believe is corrupt.
Suspected al Shabaab attack a police post with grenades, but did not cause bodily harm or property damage.
West Kenya Company farmers in Bungoma county demonstrated at the Misikhu weighbridge over reduction of cane prices by the firm. Police officers monitored the protest from a distance.

A group of 39 protesters against Kakuzi Ltd, Makuyu engage police in running battles along a road connecting Kenol and Sagana. Injuries not known or reported. The protesters qualm with the company is not known.
Migori town boda boda operators have protested against high levies by the county government. The operators held a demonstration on Administration road on Wednesday.

Al Shabaab members being held at Kamiti Maximum Security Prison riot over a cut in privileges. A warders arm was broken in the melee. Following the riot fourteen al Shabaab inmates were allegedly tortured by prison staff.
Police in Yatta stopped a demonstration against Kalonzo Musyoka by residents of Matuu town.

Residents of Narok county staged a demonstration at Duka Moja Thursday morning to protest the death of four men and a woman who died after consuming illicit brew on Wednesday night. The protesters mounted roadblocks along the Mai-Mahiu - Narok road at Duka Moja shopping centre and accused police of laxity in dealing with the sale of illicit brew.
Parents of school children block roads in protest of the appointment of a new principal of whom they disapprove.
Residents protested, calling for the arrest of a police officer after he had killed two criminals, who the protesters believe were innocent.

One civilian is killed and two police officers injured in an attack on a lorry carrying supplies for a food programme. The attackers are unknown, but are believed to be related to an ongoing clash between the Degodia and Garre clans.
A suspected rapist is lynched by a mob in Kiamburi.
Residents of Githurai again gather to protest, calling for the arrest of a police officer who they believe killed two innocents.

Transponders at the Ndarugu quarries in Juja absconded their roles for two consecutive days over a dilapidated access road. [The workers] blocked the road and demolished kiosks where the council employees collect the levies.
A group of pupils and teachers protest against a county government measure of overtake public utilities.
Police had to shoot in the air several times to quell demonstrators who blocked Thika Superhighway in Nairobi as they protested the prosecution of a police officer charged with murder.

Transponders at the Ndarugu quarries in Juja absconded their roles for two consecutive days over a dilapidated access road. [The workers] blocked the road and demolished kiosks where the council employees collect the levies.

Boda boda operators protest against a group of youth who had heckled President Uhuru at a nearby event on 08/09. [The group] marched on the Migori-Kakrao road, cursing the youth who embarrassed the Head of State.
Demonstrators protest the prosecution of a police officer for a second day. No reported police involvement.
Supporters of two teachers unions clash in Bomet, causalities, injuries not known.
Degodia fighters attack and kill two members of the Garre clan in the Darkale area of Mandera County.
Demonstrators protest the prosecution of a police officer for a third day. No reported police involvement.
A mob at Kedowa market, Kipkelion East constituency, attacked a man suspected of cow theft. They beat up Nicholas Omwenga and lynched him before setting his van on fire.
Traders at a market protest their forced relocation.
Maungu residents in Voi protested against the extraction of stones from Marasi Hill by the China Roads and Bridges Company that is constructing a railway.

Anti-terrorism police forces gun down a suspected and wanted al Shabaab member during an early morning raid on their hideout. It is believed the target of the operation was responsible for the killing of a German tourist.

Residents in Kakamega stormed Governor’s offices demanding his attention over insecurity. Carrying twigs, the protesters marched to the governor’s office after the body of a six-year-old girl was found dumped in a trench at a residential estate in Kakamega Town.
Residents of Gombato area in Diani, Kwale county lynched a suspected thief.
Residents of Emsoo ward, Keiyo North have demonstrated against the building of a planned training institute in another village.
Villagers clashed with a group of illegal sand harvesters near a bank of the Tuva river. One villager sustained a stone wound.

Residents of Garissa protest the killing of a trader at the hands of suspected Somali assailants. The protest degenerated, however, into a violent clash between Somali and non-Somali groups causing the police to the disperse the rioters with tear-gas.
At least eight are killed in twin grenade attacks in Wajir. Assailants not known.
Unidentified Somali assailants attack a kill a Garissa trader and injure two others in the early hours of the morning. Protests against this action continued throughout the day.
One person was killed and another seriously injured after a mob attacked them in Baringo under suspicion of practising witchcraft.
A man was shot dead at Lonyangelem village in West Pokot by suspected raiders from the neighbouring Turkana county.

Transport in Kabarnet town bus stage temporarily stopped when more than 200 drivers protested against hiring and firing of Baringo county vehicles drivers. The group later proceeded to the office of the Governor.

At least four people were shot and seriously wounded by police after a meeting to discuss the ouster of Makueni Governor. Those wounded include [the Governors] chief of staff, a bodyguard and two county officials who were allegedly shot when the county assemblys security personnel opened fire to disperse a charged crowd.
Students at Mathenge TTI protest a lack of a television station broadcast at their institute.

Six people have been injured in a grenade attack in Kenyas north-eastern district of Garissa. The report said a grenade was thrown by unnamed attackers on Ngamia Road near the district hospital. Though the attackers have not been identified, the source references a history of al Shabaab attacks in the area.
Students at Mucharage Girls Secondary School in Othaya went on rampage, breaking windows and staging a class walkout over the schools policy toward sick student sick leave. No injuries reported.
Students at Moi University protest over "delayed learning" after claiming they had not been taught for several months.

Residents of Mukunike village in Kilimambogo, Kiambu county protested the demolition of 50 houses by a local quarry operator. They used boulders to block the Thika-Garissa road for 3 hours bringing traffic at Kilimambogo centre to a standstill.
Residents of Mijikenda area protest over the selling of land by the local government without giving notice to the current owners.

Business on Pandit Nehru road was temporarily paralysed after hawkers evicted over "unnecessary competition" to shopkeepers. The protest engaged in running battles with police. No word of causalities or injures.
Machakos University College students protest over absentee lecturers, many of whom have not been attending classes. Six arrests reported.
Residents lynch a suspected cattle thief in Chemelil.
Dedan Kimathi University students protest over two consecutive days over delayed loans from the Higher Education Loans Board. The protests caused the institution to close on the second day.

Youth paralysed business on the Nairobi-Mombasa highway after they barricaded the road and lit fires in Voi to protest against discrimination in employment of locals at the Standard Gauge Railway project, which has employed foreign labour. No reported violence.
Dedan Kimathi University students protest over two consecutive days over delayed loans from the Higher Education Loans Board. The protests caused the institution to close on the second day.
Demonstrators protest on Nairobi (as well as other World Cities) against rhino and elephant poaching.
Two men Degodia men looking for their lost donkeys were attacked by Garre militia at Bula Dawa, Rhamu sub county, one death, one injury. The two clans have a history of rivalry.
A man was on Sunday night lynched by residents at Dallas estate in Embu town after allegedly trying to break into a womans house.
A man was lynched by residents in Nduuri village (neighbourhood), Embu East, for assaulting his mother.
Residents protest insecurity in the area. The protest comes after an increased number of armed thefts in the village in recent weeks.

A vigilante group attack a group of suspected witchdoctors at Kiptuilong village, Elgeyo Marakwet County. Some residents claimed the family had bewitched an old man in the village. Some of the victims were admitted to a hospital with serious injuries.
Boda boda motorcyclists in Kinale, Lari sub county, protest against an AP officer after an arrest of a colleague which they thought unjustified.
Residents of Kinangop in Nyandarua county held a demonstration to protest the murder of a businessman. The protesters accused a local for the death.
A section of Maseno University students engaged police in running battles in a strike due to the disruption of the student union elections by some candidates supporters. No reported injuries.
Rival Maasai groups clash over land ownership at a farm in Nakuru. One death, one injury reported.

Residents of Teso North took to the streets to protest against the state of roads in the sub county. The protest, which drew more than 100 participants from Angurai, Aedo Moru and Kakapel, blamed politicians for the poor infrastructure. The exact location of the protest was not reported.

Five passengers in two Miraa [mild narcotic] vans from Lamu to Ijara town were during the morning hours hijacked by suspected al Shabaab militia, which was later confirmed. The incident took place between Milimani and Basuba area in Lamu East sub-county. The five were taken to an unknown location. Kenyan security forces launched a search mission in response.

A police officer is killed by two suspected al Shabaab outside the Royal Court Hotel on Haile Selassie Road, Mombasa. Sources said the killing may be a revenge mission after police recently killed a man they said was a wanted suspect with links to Al-Shabaab.

Protesters blocked the Nairobi Nakuru highway at Kwambira in Limuru after a 43 year old man was found murdered near his home. The protesters lit bonfires and blocked the road with stones, accusing the government of laxity in providing security.

Drivers in Makutano and Kapenguria towns, West Pokot protested against the poor state of the Makutano-Alale road outside of Makutano. They blocked the road to the governor and county commissioners offices for several hours.
Members of the Olomismis Group Ranch in Trans Mara protested against their officials mismanagement. The exact location of the protest is not known.

Drivers in Makutano and Kapenguria towns, West Pokot protested against the poor state of the Makutano-Alale road outside of Makutano. They blocked the road to the governor and county commissioners offices for several hours.

A senior Kenyan county official escaped death narrowly after an Improvised Explosive Device (IED) exploded as he was being driven to his office in the border town of Rhamu, Mandera. Perpetrators not known. Two injuries reported.
200+ Muslims demonstrated against the 6pm-6am curfew in [Kenya] on Lamu Island. The group asserted the curfew hurts the local fishing economy.
Unknown gunmen killed a police officer near the border with Somalia before escaping.

KDF forces kill five suspected al Shabaab fighters who were attempting to drive an explosive laden car into Kenya from Ethiopia. Mandera is situated at a point where a border is shared by both Ethiopia and Somalia.

Mashujaa Day celebrations were disrupted when supporters of a Kirinyaga Central MP (TNA) engaged youths (affiliation unknown) at Kerugoya Stadium. Chaos erupted when the youths stormed the venue of the event and started booing the MP as he addressed residents. Injuries reported.

Dedan Kimathi University of Technology in Nyeri closed indefinitely following a protest by the students against the alleged incompetence of their Vice Chancellor. The over 500 students shattered window panes in lecture halls; destroyed two university buses, a private vehicle and the students welfare building; set a thicket in the school on fire and harassed motorists along Nyeri-Nyahururu highway. They later engaged armed police officers in running battles before they were dispersed with teargas. A police officer reported an injury. There were additional riots at Karatina University, also in Nyeri.

University of Eldoret students took to the streets in protest over a directive that they sit special exams. The students claimed that they were not ready for the exams and that they were not given time to prepare.

Residents of Maguguni protest along the Mombasa-Nairobi highway for five hours to protest grabbing of the land by CORD corporation leader Raila Odinga. CORD is apparently interested in petroleum prospects on the plot.
Suspected local tribesmen attack a police post in Kapedo. Five dead, including three police officers.
Twelve people were injured, four of them critically at Bula Sheikh in Garissa town when unknown assailants hurled a grenade at a shop.
A group of Muslim youth forcibly overtake a mosque in Mombasa, and ejected its moderate imam and management committee. Injuries/causalities not known.
Residents of Majengo town in Vihiga county protest, demanding an audience with the Governor of the region to express their grievance over a recent spate of robberies.

Mutige Secondary School students walked out in protest against the administrations failure to address their grievances (the students want medical attention for the injured, new toilets, transport and leakage in classrooms and dormitories fixed). The more than 200 students marched to the countys headquarters in Kerugoya.
Residents of the Milano area of Malindi town demonstrated against the buying of land by a business tycoon.
Students of Laikipia University in Kitale and Kapenguria protest the college CEOs decision to relocate them to the Eldoret campus.
Students of Laikipia University in Kitale and Kapenguria protest the college CEOs decision to relocate them to the Eldoret campus.

Lamu residents have again taken to the streets to protest the continued extension of the night curfew which has been in force for more than three months now. Police were deployed to disperse the protesters.

PERPRETATORS: Adol Clan Dinka Ethnic Militia (South Sudan)
NOTES: Nine refugees are known to have been killed and a number of others wounded in days of fighting in the Kakuma refugee camp. The fighting started after an attempted rape of a nine-year-old Nuer girl by a Dinka boy. Though the fighting mainly centered between the two South Sudanese actors, several others from Central Africa were also involved.
A vigilante mob attack and kill a robbery suspect in the Nduuri of Embu.
A vigilante mob lynch a murder suspect in Mukindu village in Ol Kalou.
Traders in Lamu protest for a second consecutive day. Police reported involvement.

PERPRETATORS: Adol Clan Dinka Ethnic Militia (South Sudan)
NOTES: Fighting between two South Sudanese tribes carries over into a second day.

Seven police members are dead and 17 missing following an attack on their post by local tribesmen. Attackers targeted three police vehicles and burned one of them. The motive for the attack is not known. A similar attack occurred in the area the previous week.
The Jomo Kenyatta University of Agriculture and Technology (JKUAT) has been closed indefinitely after students went on rampage over a fee.

At least 24 police officers and Kenya Police Reservists (KPR) are feared dead, 17 injured, in a fresh attack in Kapedo in Tiaty Sub-county Baringo County after Pokot raiders attacked the at Lomelo and Kapau areas of the city.

One person was hacked to death and four others seriously injured in a fresh attack in Bora Moyo village of Kipini. The violence began when a militia from Garjel community attacked the town when they believed its residents had stolen a herd of goats.
Six al Shabaab suspects were shot dead and a soldier seriously injured in an attempted invasion of the KDF Nyali Barracks in Mombasa early in the day.
Dock workers protest at Mombasa port against inter-political union activities.

A group of youths threw stones at Administration Police officers on night curfew patrol in Lamu. The officers were pelted with stones from a rooftop. No reported injures. The rioters were adverse to the curfew.
Residents of Homa Bay town and its environs protest against a three-day power blackout.
Residents protest against an MP over a tax law violation.
An outspoken moderate Muslim cleric and al Shabaab critic was assassinated outside his mosque in Mombasa. Perpetrators remain unknown.
Following heavy-handed treatment by police against a MP, residents of Cheptiret protest the action, calling for the local police station to be shut down. Exact date not known - source date is 07/11.

Students protest in Lodwar, Turkana county over recent insecurity in the region. The group threatened to halt oil exploration in the area if the government did not act. The protest is mainly a reaction to an attack on a police post in Kapedo over the weekend.

A security operation against a group of Pokot militia yields the recovery of weapons and the deaths of six bandits, who had been launching attacks in the area recently. An MP said banditry attacks were instigated by people who want Kapedo to be annexed to Baringo.

A Kapseret MP is slapped, pushed to the ground and stamped on the chest for refusing to comply with a police traffic order. The action spurred a protest against the police. Exact date not known - source date is 07/11.
Residents protest in Lodwar over area insecurity for a second day.

Unidentified persons shoot and kill an al Shabaab suspect in the Majengo area. The suspect was driving with his wife and niece. The assailants are rumoured to be members of a Kenyan Anti-militant unit. The killing sparked a violent protest several days later.

One is dead and several injured when a group protesting over extra-judicial killings and insecurity becomes violent. Several roads were also reported barricaded. The riot was centrally sparked to avenge the killing of terror suspect Hassan Guti. Several arrests reported.
A tribal clash over land causes the death of one and several houses destroyed. The clash occurred in Kuvasali village, Kakamega County.

At least eight people were killed and four others seriously injured in inter- communal clashes in northern Kenyas Isiolo County. The clash reportedly lasted for several hours. The clash occurred at Leruko on Isiolo side, a few meters from the bridge that connects Isiolos Buffalo Springs game reserve with Samburu Park.
Two suspected criminals were beaten up and burned by a mob in Chuka Igambangombe constituency. Police rescued the suspects, who suffered severe burns.
A womens group in suburban Nairobi protests lenient penalties on the sale of illegal alcohol.
Police raid two Kisauni mosques during the evening hours, arrest 250+ suspects. One death from the raids reported.

University of Nairobi students riot over a prolonged power blackout. The students stoned motorists driving by and robbed pedestrians who were using the road at the time of the blackout. No injuries reported.
Molasses traders protest a buyer over perceived favouritism given to conglomerates.
Hundreds of residents invaded a 60,000-acre ranch in Taita Taveta belonging to a cooperative in protest of land grabbing by a third party.
A group protests attacks on women based on wearing revealing attire.

Four are killed in Kisauni by "radical youth" on the evening of 17/11. Police suspect that the incident may have been a revenge attack for the killing of a youth at Masgid Shuhadaa during a raid on two Mosques in Kisauni the previous evening.
A mob of men attacked and stripped a woman after accusing her of being inappropriately dressed. The assault comes hours after a group protested such attacks.
At least five people were killed and four others reported missing following clashes in Dukana, Marsabit County or rights to cattle and property.
A group of internally displaced people in Gilgil protested at the office of the deputy county commissioner demanding to be given relief food.

At least 28 people were killed after suspected Al-Shabaab militants attacked a Nairobi-bound bus in Omar Jilo, Mandera County in north-east Kenya. Witness said the attackers ordered all off the bus, divided the passengers along ethnic lines - Somali and non-Somali, shooting all non-Somalis. Many of the deceased were teachers.
Residents of Embu Town on Friday night lynched a suspected mugger who had accosted a man and robbed him of his cash.

Civil society groups took to the streets, torching coffins to protest against recent Mandera violence and rising insecurity in the region. Police dispersed the crowd when they neared the Office of the President, Harambee House.
A group continues a protest against insecurity in Nairobis CBD.
Nyandarua residents protested against delay in constructing the 45km Mairo-Inya Shamata road. The residents barricaded the road for most of the day.
University of Nairobi students protest a policy that would not pay interns.
A Kenyan police officer was shot dead and another seriously wounded in an attack by suspected al Shabaab at Dadaab Refugee Camp.
A group protesting area insecurity become entangled in running battles with police. Twelve students were treated for injuries at area hospitals.
At least five people were wounded on Sunday evening after unknown men hurled a hand grenade at pedestrians in Garissa town, northern Kenya.

A pro-al Shabaab website published a report that al Shabaab has claimed the responsibility of the killing of 36-non local Kenyans at a quarry in Koromei area near Mandera in the night of 01/12. The statement claimed that the attack on Koromei was part of series of attacks executed by the Mujahidin to serve as a response to Kenyas occupation of Somalia, the airstrikes by Kenyan warplanes and the killing of innocent Somalis.
At least one patron is killed when suspected al Shabaab attack a country club bar in Wajir. Witnesses claim two blasts followed by gunfire.
Hundreds of women staged a demonstration to protest against their husbands neglect of family responsibilities.
Protesters against insecurity throw stones at a bus and raid a Somali-owned hotel in Mwingi. Police shot into the air to disperse the mob.
Al Shabaab lines and executes 15 non-Muslim farmers by firing squad in Mado Gashi.

An unknown assailant threw two grenades into a cafe in Garissa on Wednesday night, wounding two people. The source references several attacks from al Shabaab in the area, but does not speculate as to who is responsible for the Wednesday blast.
Elegeyo-Marakwet residents protest over a road overgrown with foliage, causing passage difficult.
Residents of Matuu town, Machakos county, took to the streets to protest demolition of kiosks by the county government.
Students of Egerton University riot over persistent power outages. Property was destroyed, two buildings were set on fire and students looted shops. Ten arrests. No reported injuries.

An explosive device is discovered in Kenyatta Barracks along the Gilgil-Nyahururu road. The device was discovered before it could be detonated. Perpetrators not known. Date not provided - source dated 08/12.

Nandi militia attack the Luhya village of Kuvasali (Obasari) in a suspected revenge attack. The violence, which broke up at 9a.m. [0600 gmt] has seen over 20 houses burnt, animals killed and plantations torched by attackers. Many residents fled the area. Causalities not reported.
Kibabii University is closed indefinitely following a student riot over postponed exams. The school is believed to have postponed the exams due to the non-payment of tuition from several students.
The source reports six have died at the hands of vigilantes over the past six days in West Sabatia, Vihiga County. Specific dates of each instance are not known.

Gunmen attack and killed a police officer and wound two others in Kilifi during the overnight hours. There was no immediate claim of responsibility, but previous attacks have been blamed on Islamist groups accused of links to Somalias Al-Qaeda-affiliated Shebab rebels, or to a separatist movement called the Mombasa Republican Council (MRC).
Residents of Kainuk protest insecurity in their area after a spate of increased armed banditry along the Lodwa-Kitale road.
Two people were injured as herders from the Tugen community battled suspected Pokot bandits. The battle broke out at Chemoe, near the Baringo North and Tiaty subcounty border.
Two IEDs are discovered by police in Nairobi (Mlango Kubwa and Pangani areas). One or both were destroyed with a controlled explosion.
One man was seriously injured and property worth thousands of shillings destroyed after members of the Kikuyu and Maasai communities clashed over a parcel of land near Eburu Forest.
At least ten people are killed following two days of ethnic clashes in Kinango, Kwale County. Both communities claimed grazing rights on a ranch.
At least ten people are killed following two days of ethnic clashes in Kinango, Kwale County. Both communities claimed grazing rights on a ranch.

A man was beaten to death and set on fire by residents in Riandu village, Mbeere North subcounty after it became believed he assaulted a small boy. The date of the attack is not known - the source is dated 18/12.
About 600 members of the Ogiek community evicted from Cengalo forest in South Nandi catchment area protested along the nearby Kapsabet-Nabkoi highway against lack of compensation.
A man has been lynched in Kaloleni village, Masii location, Mwala district after he was caught with two stolen hens.
Suspected al Shabaab attack a Lamu bound bus in Nyangoro. Four shots were reported fired, though no one was reported injured.

Unknown people hurled a grenade on the evening of 21/12 at a residential area in Mandera. The explosive was targeted at a group of people who were chewing miraa at Green View near the National Cereals and Produce Board depot around 7pm. No one was injured.
A hotel security guard is shot and killed and his colleague injured after ten gunmen dressed in police uniform attacked the two in Diani. Perpetrators not identified.

One police reservist has been killed and another injured in Wajir. The report says weapons belonging to the two policemen were taken away by the unnamed attackers. Al Shabaab claimed responsibility several days following the incident.

A prominent cleric is kidnapped and later found dead (28/12). Perpetrators not known, though Muslim leaders blame police forces for his death. Further, it is not known if the kidnapping has any connection the killing of two women the same day elsewhere in the town.
Two women are killed by unknown gunmen on Garissa.
Police and a group of journalists clash after police objected to a story they were covering. Injuries not known.
An irate mob in Nyatike killed a suspected cattle thief while two of his colleagues escaped with serious injuries on [the afternoon of (28/12).

About 200 residents of Ngangarithi held a demonstration in Nyeri town over the proposed new land rates. The residents opposed the new rates in the County Finance Revenue Bill, saying the increased taxation is too high.
A burnt mans body is discovered at a coffee plantation near Kangaru in Engu. Perpetrators not known. The time of death may have been up to three days before its discovery on 03/01.
Boda boda riders and traders protest a new law that prohibits animals to travel through the CBD of Bomet.

Youths took to Ngong Road in Nairobi and adjacent streets to protest the death of former Prime Minister Raila Odingas son, who died in unclear circumstances. The protesters demanded to know the cause of death. The demo lasted several hours.
Teachers strike, protest over poor working conditions.
Pokot gunmen killed a school guard during the late morning hours. Motive unknown.
Hundreds of Athi River sub county workers protested over a irregular payment from Machakos county government.
Medical worker protesters clash with a group that was attempting to stop them. One man is injured after he was hit in the face with a stone.
More than 1,000 teachers from Buuri, North Imenti, South Imenti and Meru Central sub counties protest in Meru. The teachers were on strike, calling for better salaries.
Following an attack by armed robbers in Ol Moran village of Laikipia residents protest insecurity.
Traders at Kalundu market held a demonstration in Kitui town, protesting against high market charges by the county government.
Fishermen clash with police after officials closed a corridor leading to Lake Naivasha and Karagita beach in Naivasha. No reported injuries.
Two demonstrators were shot and injured by police in Mau Narok during a protest against increased road accidents.

An unidentified attacker targeted a crowded Mombasa church, but are repulsed by police guarding the door. Police engaged the assailant in a shootout before he escaped. The reason for the attack is not known. One church official was reported dead following the incident.

Pokot cattle rustlers struck Namawanga village inhabited by members of the Luhya community and shot dead a local farmer before stealing three bulls from his home. In revenge, Luhya tribesmen hacked to death a Pokot man after they found him ferrying two passengers to Karnyarkwat market. The killing of the man sparked off protest from members of the Pokot community who thronged to Kapkoi market vowing to revenge over the killing of their tribesmen.
URP supporters disrupt a demonstration in Bomet concerning the location of a university, no reported violence. Police forces dispersed the two groups.

Pokot cattle rustlers struck Namawanga village inhabited by members of the Luhya community and shot dead a local farmer before stealing three bulls from his home. In revenge, Luhya tribesmen hacked to death a Pokot man who operates a motor cycle taxis after they found him ferrying two passengers to Karnyarkwat market. The killing of the man sparked off protest from members of the Pokot community who thronged to Kapkoi market vowing to revenge over the killing of their tribesmen.

Pokot cattle rustlers struck Namawanga village inhabited by members of the Luhya community and shot dead a local farmer before stealing three bulls from his home. In revenge, Luhya tribesmen hacked to death a Pokot man who operates a motor cycle taxis after they found him ferrying two passengers to Karnyarkwat market. The killing of the man sparked off protest from members of the Pokot community who thronged to Kapkoi market vowing to revenge over the killing of their tribesmen.
A group of Nairobi-based journalists were ejected from a reception area at the United Nations complex in Kenyas capital after launching a protest over Al-Jazeera journalists jailed in Egypt.
Suburban Nairobi residents set a suspected thief alight.
Residents of Machakos hurled stones at county Askaris to stop them from towing away the deputy governors car. A woman broke her leg when she was allegedly beaten by the Askaris.
The Kenya Defence Forces killed eight al Shabaab and injured several others during an encounter with the insurgents in Basuba, Lamu county. A KDF soldier died while three others were injured.
Githurai residents on 15/01 morning lynched four people who they accused of engaging in criminal activities in the area.
A group of women protesting in support of circumcision of girls lured activists opposed to the practice and attacked them at Enoosaen Village in Transmara, Narok County. Injuries not known.
Two groups of protesters clash - those for and against a withdrawal of Sh60 million annual sponsorship for four schools in Mtwapa. Injuries not known.

Students and activists protesting against a school land dispute clash with police Langata. Rocks thrown, tear gas implemented. Five pupils, two journalists and a police officer were injured and two activists arrested during the incident. The event became a scandal in the following days after it was learned that several of the injured students were young children.
Three unidentified gunmen shoot and kill an Imam at a construction site in Likoni. Investigators have not established a motive.
Protesting the availability of jobs offered by a power company, residents block the a road leading to work site in Kargi for several days, holding hostage a truck driver ferrying supplies.
Boda boda operators in Amagoro town protest alleged police harassment.
Protesting the availability of jobs offered by a power company, residents block the a road leading to work site in Kargi for several days, holding hostage a truck driver ferrying supplies.
Three men are killed when Kikuyu and Maasai groups clashed over a farms ownership.
Protesting the availability of jobs offered by a power company, residents block the a road leading to work site in Kargi for several days, holding hostage a truck driver ferrying supplies.
Protesting the availability of jobs offered by a power company, residents block the a road leading to work site in Kargi for several days, holding hostage a truck driver ferrying supplies.
Students of Limuko Secondary School in Bahati protest, demanding the transfer of their principal alleging "highhandedness."
Transporters blocked the highway near Mlolongo on 26/01 to protest the closing of access roads by police, who they charged with corruption.

At least two people were feared dead and dozens others wounded in Narok when protests to oust Governor Samuel Tunai turned chaotic. The protesters accused the governor of corruption. Among those wounded was area police chief Paul Letting and two of his juniors, police said of the protests, which brought Narok town to a standstill for several hours. At least one of the dead was shot by police. Several arrests were recorded in the following days, including five Senators.
A group of Boba Boda operators lynch a 16-year old girl of suspected theft.

Protestors in Narok county on Wednesday night blocked roads in the area after Senator Stephen Ole Ntutu and four legislators were earlier arrested over demonstrations that occurred on Monday. The protestors who were armed with sticks and arrows blocked the road in Ololunga area and another in Katagala for more than two hours over the arrests, demanding their release. Police had to fire tear gas at the protestors to disperse them.

Protestors in Narok county on Wednesday night blocked roads in the area after Senator Stephen Ole Ntutu and four legislators were earlier arrested over demonstrations that occurred on Monday. The protestors who were armed with sticks and arrows blocked the road in Ololunga area and another in Katagala for more than two hours over the arrests, demanding their release. Police had to fire tear gas at the protestors to disperse them.
Students in Wajir protest a teacher shortage in the area.

Protesters continue their demonstration against the detention of a group of lawmakers. Protestors blocked traffic on the Nairobi-Narok highway, police responded with teargas and live fire, clashes followed. No reported deaths.
Political activists (affiliation not known) march in Kapsabet for unknown reason.

Nairobi Aviation College students blocked Kimathi Street to protest an unflattering expose on sale of certificates aired on television. The students, who carried twigs and college banners, threw stones at Nation Centre breaking doors and windows and chased journalists who were taking pictures. Police dispersed the students twice, the second time after they had regrouped. Tear gas used. 12 arrests reported.
800 Mandera teachers protest al Shabaab spurred insecurity in their region at the KNUT headquarters in Nairobi. After several hours the group marched to the parliament building.
A suspect in the murder of a boda boda operator in Sindo, Suba subcounty, was snatched from the police by residents and beaten to death in Sindo.

Four killed and several injured during a Pokot raid on a Turkana village. Authorities claimed the attacks were meant to scare members of the Turkana community into leaving Lomelo, Silale and Nadome villages, which Pokots have laid claim.

Police have fired in the air and lobbed teargas to disperse hundreds of City Park Market traders who are protesting the burning down of their stalls, which they claim was sabotage. The traders blocked Limuru Road to traffic, demanding compensation from the government after the fire destroyed their goods and other properties. The rioters threw stones at passing motorists and police.

Police fired teargas at students of Kenya Medical Training College who were protesting over the death of their classmate. The student had committed suicide after being removed from an exam over unpaid fees.

Three people were critically injured after a hand grenade was hurled at a food kiosk in Mandera town. The reason for the attack is not known. The perpetrators escaped. Authorities suspect one of the victims may have been linked to al Shabaab.

A group of cattle herdsmen blocked the Mai Mahiu-Narok road (B3) for several hours after several of the herd were killed when they were hit with a lorry. The herdsmen demanded compensation for their loss by the colliding driver. They barred police officers from removing the truck or the carcasses until the matter was resolved.

Traders pelted Nairobi Governor Evans Kidero with mud during an appearance. The traders stalls were burned the previous evening for which the traders blamed the local government. The governors bodyguards shot into the air to disperse the mob.

Traders in Molo town held a demonstration to protest against the poor state of the Molo-Kibunjia road. The traders barricaded the road with stones and flaming tyres, saying the government is deliberately ignoring them.

A prominent Kenyan MP of the Jubilee Coalition (George Muchai) was shot dead along with two bodyguards and a driver in the centre of Nairobi in the early hours of 07/02. The masked perpetrators, who were driving an automobile with Ugandan licence plates, escaped. A senior police officer said the killing looked like an execution-style hit.
Residents of Kabete constituency held a demonstration at Wangige trading centre over the pace of investigations into area MP George Muchais murder, which occurred on 07/02.

Traders of Burma Market, Nairobi used flaming tyres to block Jogoo Road in a demo against alleged land grabbing on [the morning of 13/02]. The traders hurled stones at motorists preventing access to the road and causing a traffic snarl up. [The rioters] engaged police in running battles as tear gas canisters were lobbed to disperse them.
Police in Thika shot in the air to disperse a crowd who had planned on attacking an officer who they believed had earlier assaulted a woman.
Unknown assailants on the evening of 13/02 hurled two hand grenades at police officers on patrol in Wajir town. No reported injuries.

Embu Governor Martin Wamboras supporters (TNA) and those of Runyenjes MP Cecily Mbarire (Party of National Unity) clash. Wamboras supporters were demonstrating against the High Courts decision to remove Wambora from office when those supporters of Mbarire attacked the group leading to melee. The two groups engaged in running battles before riot police intervened. Injuries not reported.
Residents of Umande, Laikipia East sub county, held a demonstration against the abstraction of Sirimon River by a privately held dam.
A mob stones a suspected murderer to death.

Groups of students clashed along ethnic lines with "members of the community" over the removal of the universitys vice chancellor over alleged sexual misconduct and murder. The identities of the ethnic groups are not known. No reported injuries or causalities in the second melee.

A Senator and ten others are assaulted by riot police when they staged a protest at the University of Eldoret in an effort to force the removal of the vice chancellor Teresa Akenga, whom area leaders accused of nepotism and skewed employment. The protest was reported as peaceful.
A boda boda operator was killed by colleagues and his body set on fire (18/02) on the Webuye-Malaba road at Chekulo, Bungoma. The victim was suspected of murder.
Students protest violently for a second day against sexual misconduct alleged against a school leader.
Hundreds of Voi residents took to the streets on 19/02 in a protest for the arrest of a Marungu ward rep over alleged sexual abuse.
Residents of Ukasi, Mwingi Central, hold a peaceful demonstration to protest against prolonged water shortage.
Street traders hold a "mostly peaceful" demonstration in Kutui over a tax levied against them. No report of violence.

Farmers blocked the Nairobi-Naivasha highway in Kinangop for more than four hours protesting a wind project which they allege would displace several families. During the protest, a house and a vehicle were burnt down as the farmers engaged police in running battles. There were unconfirmed reports that two women and a boy were rushed to a private hospital with bullet wounds.

University of Nairobi students protested the death of their colleague who succumbed to injuries following an pedestrian-auto accident last week. The students pelted vehicles passing through Waiyaki Way and University Way with stones, causing a traffic problems.
Farmers protest in Kinangop for a second day, engage in running battles with police. One dead, several others injured.

More than 200 businesspeople in Kisii town staged a demonstration to protest against grabbing of land where they operate. The traders protested against a decision by the county government to move them from outside the Kisii Municipal Market.
Three quarters of students at Leshau Boys High School boycotted classes, protesting alleged poor hygiene in the institution. The students marched peacefully to the Nyahururu-Nyeri highway.
Boda boda drivers protest a tax increase over two consecutive days in Mumias.
Tugan and Pokot militias exchange fire over grazing land and cattle ownership at Kapndasum in Marigat. An unarmed bystander was killed in the shootout, several others missing.

One person was killed and two others injured in an attack by suspected Al-Shabaab gunmen in Mandera Town on the night of 25/02. The victims were witnessed crossing from nearby Somalia at an earlier date and are suspected to be Somalis
Boda boda drivers protest a tax increase over two consecutive days in Mumias.
Television viewers protest analogue signal switch off at outside Communications Authority offices on Waiyaki Way, Nairobi. The switch off forces viewers to purchase a digital apparatus.
A vigilante group attack and sets alight four robbery suspects at different nearby locations: Three in Kathiani and one in Kituvu.
A vigilante group attack and sets alight four robbery suspects at different nearby locations: Three in Kathiani and one in Kituvu.

Students of ST Mathias Busia Boys Secondary School strike over test grades, vandalise school property, broke into teachers residential houses, staff rooms, offices, and stores, the canteen and laboratories. No reported injury.
Following an road accident involving students, students of Thiru Secondary School barricade a road in protest.
Students of Chebara Boys Secondary School, Marakwet West, held a demonstration, demanding the removal of principal, whom they accused of mismanagement.
Teachers of a Mandera school are attacked and injured when students from a neighbouring school targeted them in blame for the cancellation of recent exams.
Students of Kilgoris Boys National School pelt their principals home with stones following learning of poor exam results.
Residents of Mukurwe-ini marched to the sub-county hospitals mortuary and took away the body of a man who was allegedly shot by a police officer in protest of the killing.
Residents of Tseikuru protest, demand the removal of the local district commissioner. Police dispersed the group.
More than 200 Kisii county government employees demonstrated at Governor James Ongwaes office protesting they have not been paid for nine months.
Two unidentified sub tribes clash over land at Kathanje (Kathangei), Chuka Igambangombe constituency. One death, plus other injuries reported.
A vigilante mob attacks and nearly killed a suspected cattle thief at Likuyani subcounty, Kakamega.

West Pokot county residents held a demonstration to protest against increase in road accidents on the Kitale-Lodwar road. The residents barricaded the road for the better part of the day, halting transport. They felled big trees on the road, blocking it completely at Kamatira market. Kamatira Primary School pupils also joined the demonstration, saying many of their colleagues have died on the road.
Traders protest an eviction notice along the Malaba-Eldoret road.
Al Shabaab attack, and then later claim responsibility for the death of four in Wajir. Three other injured.

Three people were killed and eight more wounded when al Shabaab launched a cross-border raid on a convoy carrying Mandera county governor Ali Roba. The governor escaped unharmed. The convoy was travelling either to or from Nairobi.
Employees of Kenya Methodist University protest a reduction of their allowances by the institution.
Al Shabaab carries out the second attack in two days in Mandera. One death, three injuries reported. In the following days the death total was raised from 1 to 4.
An IED explodes in Mandera following a similar attack across the Somali border in Beled Hawo. No reported causalities.
Four are killed and their bodies burnt in a grenade attack on a Wajir shop. Perpetrators not known.
The Member of County Assembly for Korogocho was shot and killed during an attack in Ruaraka, Nairobi on the morning of 18/03. The motive for the attack is not known.

A riotous mob attacked a man, killed him and burnt down his house (in Itumbu) after suspecting him of being in a criminal gang. The attack came after villagers carried out a violent protest against insecurity in the region. A protester was injured after the suspects son tried to stop them from burning their house. A similarly motivated protest occurred the previous day. The protesters burnt three houses belonging to a family suspected of harbouring a criminal gang.
Hundreds of Mandera County residents took to the streets of the border town on 20/03 protesting over recent insecurity in the area. The protesters called for the removal of the county commissioner.

A riotous mob attacked a man, killed him and burnt down his house (in Itumbu) after suspecting him of being in a criminal gang. The attack came after villagers carried out a violent protest against insecurity in the region. A protester was injured after the suspects son tried to stop them from burning their house. A similarly motivated protest occurred the previous day. The protesters burnt three houses belonging to a family suspected of harbouring a criminal gang.
Residents of Mandera County demonstrate against recent area violence by al Shabaab. Date not known: source dated 21/03.

A riotous mob attacked a man, killed him and burnt down his house (in Itumbu) after suspecting him of being in a criminal gang. The attack came after villagers carried out a violent protest against insecurity in the region. A protester was injured after the suspects son tried to stop them from burning their house. A similarly motivated protest occurred the previous day. The protesters burnt three houses belonging to a family suspected of harbouring a criminal gang.
A groups of youths protest the Mandera Deputy Governor during a rally in Mandara.
Students of Rongo University College state a protest after a residential hall is burned. The protest and fire may be related to a recent election which caused tension in the area.
Parents of two schools in Nakuru hold a demonstration to protest the grabbing of a section of the school land by a private developer.

Residents violently protest the release of two murder suspects on bond. The protesters blocked the nearby Eldoret-Chavakali road for hours and injured one police officer. Additionally, several shops and houses were burned.
A woman was killed, allegedly by police, during a demonstration in Malindi to protest against the tax increase by the Kilifi county government. Police deny they used live rounds.
A suspected murderer is lynched by a vigilante group in Mukuro.
Fruit factory workers protest poor working conditions in Bibirioni, Limuru. Date not clear - source dated 24/03.
Traders blocked the Eldoret-Nakuru highway at Burnt Forest, protesting against increased licence fees and poor services.
A senior Mombasa police detective is gunned down in an apparent well organized assassination. The perpetrator is not unknown, though the source cites al Shabaab presence in the area.
A vigilante mob "last week" lynched a criminal suspect. Source dated 31/03.

A group of Kenyan youths protest a Chinese Restaurants policy of refusing entry to local people during the nigh time hours. The protest turned violent, however, when the group began looting the restaurant. No injury reported.
Baringo county residents protest reoccurring attack by Pokot bandits. The protesters marched throughout the county, eventually ending in Kabarnet.
Hundreds of travellers heading to either Tanzania or Kenya are stranded at Namanga border after Kajiado residents blocked the road to protest over a missing taxi driver.
Three suspected carjackers are lynched by a mob in Kariene, Meru County.
Two groups of demonstrators in Kilifi clashed outside the Kilifi police station as they differed over whether Governor Amason Kingi should step aside over corruption allegations.

At least one person was killed and three others injured on the morning of 01/04 when masked gunmen attacked a non-governmental organisations compound at the Dadaab Refugee Camp. The attack occurred during the early morning hours, perpetrators not known.

Al Shabaab gunmen attack Garissa University during the morning hours in an operation that lasted the majority of the day. Four attackers were killed during the siege, and the police are holding another five individuals for questioning.

Al Shabaab gunmen attack Garissa University during the morning hours in an operation that lasted the majority of the day. Almost all of the 148 people killed were students and another 79 people were injured.
Garissa residents protest a recent al Shabaab attack on a school in their town. Date unknown - source dated 04/04.
Hundreds of Kenyan residents have rallied at a state sponsored protest in the capital Nairobi to condemn recent Al-Shabaab attack on Gaarisa University premises.
Hundreds of Somalis took to the streets in the Nairobis Somali-dominated Eastleigh neighbourhood on Sunday [5 April] to protest against the recent deadly attack on Garissa university.

Police impounded a suspicious vehicle and arrested a unidentified woman when it is suspected she was to bomb an Easter church service in Mombasa. Two additional suspects fled the area. No injuries reported.
Factory workers protest a dispute with management.
Students protest the Garissa attack in Nairobi, calling on the government to do more for security.
Traders in Limuru protest increased fees. Date(s) not known - the protest was described as "ongoing."

The bodies of two men are discovered in Kamirithu village on the morning of 08/04. Their deaths may have occurred the evening before. The motive of the attack as well as their identifies of the victims are not known.
Traders in Kisii protest a tax increase.
Protesters of police practices stone a journalist covering the event. The journalist suffered a head and knee injury.
Kenyan police on 11/04 shot dead two al Shabaab suspects in an incident that left one police officer injured in Kwale.
Police uncover and remove an IED in Mandera County, near the Somali border on 12/04.
Pokot militia kill a goat herder in Chemoe.
A mob lynched two suspected cattle thieves in Likuyani subcounty, Kakamega.
A suspected rustler was killed by a mob in Central Kanyamkago ward, Uriri subcounty in Migori county. One of his accomplices was injured while the rest escaped.

Transport on the Nairobi-Mai Mahiu road in Lari constituency, Kiambu county was disrupted by a four hour demonstration (it is not clear if the demonstrators blocked the roadway) by transporters of building materials. They were protesting the new Sh400 per trip levy.
Traders protest county taxes in Thika.
Ten armed members of al Shabaab hijack a bus carrying ten passengers, deboard them and take the bus across the border into Somalia. No violence reported.
Hospital workers protest unpaid dues.

Boda Boda operators block a road and light fires in protest against a police "crackdown" against them. They said police ask for bribes and frequently arrest them for no genuine reason. A similar protest was held the following day in a nearby area.
Boda Boda operators protest alleged police harassment by barricading the Narok-Bomet road.
10,000 members of the National Hospital Insurance Fund in Nyandarua county protest against a rate increase in Ndunyu Nderu.

Heavily armed gunmen suspected to be members of Al-Shabaab on the morning of 23/04 kidnapped senior Arabia chief in Mandera County along the Mandera-Arabia road. The chief was driven across the border into Somalia where he was killed at Gadoon Dhowe, Beled Xawo District.
Suspected Somali Al-Shabaab kidnapped two Kenyan teachers on the evening of 24/04 in the Mandera border town.
The more than 100 traders held a demonstration in Gakindu town over a closed slaughterhouse that they claim cannot be reopened due to bureaucratic oversight.
Residents of Ndagani, in Igambangombe constituency on the morning of 27/04 blocked the Meru- Nairobi highway to protest against the poor sate of Ndagani-Gicusa road.
Workers protest poor working conditions and pay in Jomvu.
Hundreds of traders from Nairobis Woodley-Jamhuri market protested alleged grabbing of their market by a private developer.

At least fifteen people are feared dead in fresh attack among rival villages or groups in Baragoi, Samburu County. Eight people were reportedly killed during a raid at Lomirok early Sunday morning (03/05). Unconfirmed reports indicate that another six, among them women and children, were killed at Sarma along the Samburu-Marsabit border that evening.
Residents protest against Baringo county insecurity in Marigat.

Turkana raiders attack a Pokot village close to Nadome along the Turkana-East Pokot district border, killing 18 residents. Following the attack a Pokot militia assembled, chasing the attackers to nearby Kogh-Tuw village and killing 36.

Turkana raiders attack a Pokot village close to Nadome along the Turkana-East Pokot district border, killing 18 residents. Following the attack a Pokot militia assembled, chasing the attackers to nearby Kogh-Tuw village and killing 36.
A resident is shot and killed when a group resisted a forced eviction. Following the shooting tenants lit fires and sang anti-oppression themed songs.
Tenants continue protests for a second day following a forced eviction and resident shooting. No violence reported.
Nurses at Meru teaching hospital protest over non-payment of salaries.
Women in Makueni county held a peaceful demonstration to oppose a bill on the implementation of the two-thirds gender rule. The protest took place in Wote town.
Two suspected Al-Shabab gunmen and a police officer killed in shoot out at Dadaab Hamey Patrol Base in Garissa.
Residents protest the removal of a roadblock by police believing the action to be "suspect."
Police clash with students protesting the death of colleague, seven injuries reported.
Ethiopian soldiers armed with AK-47 rifles cross into Kenya aboard 10 vehicles and reportedly take over a police station in North Horr.

Following the disappearance of three people residents of Kinna protest, accusing the Kenya Wildlife Service of kidnapping. The residents marched to the Meru National Park and allegedly set a fire at the park. One is killed and eleven injured after the police engaged the protesters.
Residents of Muoroto Kamiti village in Kiambu Town constituency protest against the grabbing of 2,400 acres by a private developer.
Al Shabaab "catches two military posts (in Sangailu and Hulugho) by surprise," no violence reported.
Al Shabaab "catches two military posts (in Sangailu and Hulugho) by surprise," no violence reported.
Residents of Kiangage in Muranga on the night of 19/05 set ablaze a matatu driver that killed a boda boda rider in a recent accident.
Al Shabaab gunmen attack Yumbis and Wel Marer villages in Fafi, each about 80 Km north east of Garissa. Security forces pushed back the attackers, no reported causalities.
Al Shabaab gunmen attack Yumbis and Wel Marer villages in Fafi, each about 80 Km north east of Garissa. Security forces pushed back the attackers, no reported causalities.
Al Shabaab attacks a police post Yumbis on the night of 25/05, killing 20. Al Shabaab had also attacked the area the previous week.

Transport on Moi South Lake road in Naivasha was paralysed for more than three hours as residents protested the closure of a public corridor leading to Lake Naivasha. The more than 400 residents blocked the road using boulders and light fires to protest the closure demanded justice. Police entered the area and engaged the demonstrators in running battles. Spats of violence continued into the second day. "Scores" injured.

Residents protested for a second day against the closure of a public corridor leading to Lake Naivasha. The more than 400 residents blocked the road using boulders and light fires to protest the closure demanded justice. Police entered the area and engaged the demonstrators in running battles. Spats of violence continued into the second day. "Scores" injured.
Unidentified gunmen shoot and kill an off-duty police officer of the anti-radicalisation squad at close range in Kibokoni, outside of Mombasa.
Al Shabaab creates a heavy presence in Lafey village effectively "taking over" the village. The presence of al Shabaab caused several villagers to flee for safety.

Two non-local residents of Marsabit are killed in mysterious circumstances by unidentified assailants. Non-locals claim that they are being targeted in assassinations by police. The police deny the allegations.
At least three people were killed and several others injured on the morning of 06/06 in inter-community clashes at Lowangila in Isiolo County. The clash may be related to rights to cattle or land.

Suspected al Shabaab opened fire at a residential area of Wajir on 06/06, killing three persons. Officials and residents said the attackers were believed to have been seeking to kill a local administrator who lives close to the scene of the attack and is known to be on an al Shabaab "wanted" list for speaking out against the sects activities in the region.

Al Shabaab reportedly erects a series of road blocks between Garba Tula and Modogashe townships [north-eastern Kenya] for purposes of extorting money from motorists. Despite these assertions, the local government denies these claims. Exact date unknown.

Hundreds of residents of Dadaab took to the streets on 06/08 to protest over the alleged sacking of 13 local employees by the World Food Programme (WFP). Waving placards, demonstrators marched through the town before heading to the main UNHCR headquarters offices gate where they camped for several hours.
Youth employed to repair roads at Jomvu in Mikindani, Mombasa county held a protest march on 08/06 over delayed pay.

At least 10 pastoralists from Isiolo have been killed in clashes with Laikipia residents after the herders invade the area with hundreds of animals. The herders also shot two security personnel after they were ordered to vacate the land during the clashes.
Residents of Baraka Estate protest over poor roads in their area.
Marsabit non-local residents protest over insecurity following a recent spate of killings in which they were targeted.

Al Shabaab attacks several locations of Lamu Island and were able to briefly overtake the area known as "Mangai," an area they found with little resistance. Other places attacked included a school and a military camp. Military forces eventually repelled the attackers. "Several" casualties reported, eleven of which were recorded as al Shabaab. Later reports suggest a British-born member of al Shabaab (known as Thomas Evans or Abdul Akim) may have been a leader in the attack and is among the dead. Another suspect of the attack was apprehended on 20/06.
Residents of Salgaa Township, Nakuru blocked Nakuru-Eldoret highway accusing the Governor of denying them development. Several vehicles were reportedly burnt during the protest.

Five pastoralists are killed by unidentified gunmen at Wari walo village some 10 kilometres from Kenya border. Those killed were three children (two boys and a girl), their father and a close relative. The five had recently left Elmole in pursuit of pasture and water for their animals.

Police in Siaya were forced to shoot in the air several times when a group of "rowdy" youths disrupted a meeting chaired by Governor Cornel Rasanga in Yala. Chanting anti-Rasanga slogans, the group claimed the governor had no place in Yala, which is in Gem constituency. No causalities reported.

20 people are killed in Durogo [phonetic] in Mandera County in what has been described as revenge attacks by Garre [clan] fighters following the killings of their clansmen. Perpetrators are not known. Date unclear - source dated 17/06.
Hospital staff protest staff leadership in the suburban Nairobi area of Moi on 19/06.
Suspected al Shabaab shot and killed a chief of Erib location in Wajir on 20/06.
Two university students are lynched by a vigilante group over suspected theft "at the weekend."

Youth demonstrators protesting against National Youth Service slum projects as well as against Devolution Cabinet Secretary Ann Waiguru. The youth started demonstrating at 7pm at Kiberas Olympic stage, where they lit bonfires and barricaded the road. The group believed the NYS and Waiguru are corrupt. The protests may have continued the following day, as there was a reported heavy police presence.
Three KDF members are injured in an al Shabaab IED attack Milimani on 21/06.
Residents from Obunga slums in Kisumu on 22/06 held demonstrations in support of a politician they believed is being unfairly criticised.

Youths attached to the National Youth Service slum-upgrading project in Kisumu on 23/06 staged a demo in Nairobi centre to protest against calls by Cord leaders that the project be investigated on financial corruption grounds.
Staff of a garment company in Athi River protest after the suspension of their chief shop steward.
