One person was killed and two others injured in an attack by suspected Al-Shabaab gunmen in Mandera Town on the night of 26/06. All of the victims are "non-locals," origin not known.
Parents of Muslim students in Kwale protest after it is alleged their children were forced to attend church services while attending school.

Youths from Chuka Igambangombe Constituency demonstrated in Chuka Town during recruitment by the National Youth Service, criticizing the criteria used to fill the 1,440 vacancies. The protest lasted the majority of the afternoon.

Residents of Isiolo town in Eastern Province held a demo on 30/06 over the disappearance and abduction of several men. Hundreds of women held a peaceful rally demanding answers from the government. Many of the protesters accused the Kenya Wildlife Services for the disappearance of the men.
Hundreds of boda boda operators hold a demonstration outside City Hall in Nairobi accusing city askaris of harassment.
Nine are killed and six others injured on 01/07 following an attack by members of the Marhani clan of Somalia on Arabia.
A senior, off-duty National Intelligence Service officer is shot and killed on 03/07 by two unidentified assailants in Mombasa.
A suspected murderer is lynched in Ganze.
A group protests against homosexuality in Nairobi.

Al Shabaab attacks Mandera town, throwing grenades into homes while people slept on 07/07. 14 dead. Al Shabaab later officially claimed responsibility, declaring they were specifically targeting Christians.

Armed men attacked a passenger bus on 07/07 at Mpekatoni border town. There were no immediate reports of any casualties. Police later report the attack was not carried out by al Shabaab, but rather an unidentified group of locals.
Students from Nguviu Boys High School in Embu North shattered window panes of their buildings for allegedly being refused to eat directly from sufurias.
Al Shabaab attacks a police convoy, including a civilian bus travelling in Mkunumbi, no reported causalities.
Al Shabaab targets police with an IED in Lamu on 13/07. Three deaths reported.
One person dies in a clash between the Kabasiran and Kapkeny clans in Elgeyo Marakwet.
Another person dies in a clan war over land on 12/07.
Students in Likoni violently protest over delayed syllabus completion ahead of an exam.
Groups students of Moi University clash violently over forthcoming student elections, destroying property. Police engaged the rioters and made several arrests.
Students of Gatamaiyu Boys High School riot, destroy school property. Authorities were not clear as to the reason of the protest.
Reports indicate that Al Shabaab overtook Milimani village in Lamu on the night of 18/07. No violence was reported.
Students from Njoro Boys High School in Nakuru riot over a water supply problem.

More than 600 workers of the China Road and Bridges Company demonstrated on 20/07 against denial of a pay rise to 500 workers. The protest blocked the Nairobi - Mombasa highway at Athi River Steel Plant for an hour. Protesting workers were dispersed by police.
Students of Technical University of Kenya embark of a violent protest over "a stalemate surrounding the validity of the courses." Police dispersed the protesters following some property damage.
Residents of Athi River protest the police release of a man accused of rape.
Students of St Pauls Kiwanjani Secondary School protest violently after several students were sent home over disciplinary action. A teacher was reportedly assaulted.
KDF soldiers killed three al Shabaab when they repulsed an attack at Basuba, Lamu county, on Wednesday (29/07) morning. Three members of the military forces were injured.
A tussle over the leadership of a church in Vihiga. A house and automobile were destroyed the subsequent unrest.
A members of the National Intelligence Service is killed when a vigilante mob mistook him for a criminal in the Bu‎ruburu area.

Nine are dead and six are injured in a fight between pastoralists and farmers in Tana River. Additionally, several houses were destroyed. The clashes between Wardei pastoralists and Mijikenda farmers occurred in Wachu Oda in Garsen. A reported 1,500 people displaced as a result of the clashes.
An al Shabaab-planted explosive attached to a military vehicle causes seven soldier deaths.
Turkana attackers kill five in a suspected cattle rustling operation. The attack caused tension in the area.
Al Shabaab forces briefly take over Basuba in Lamu Country. Once there, al Shabaab leaders addressed the town and met with elders before retreating.
Two groups of churchgoers clash over the rights to a building.
Female APs took to the streets of Kakamega town on 17/08, in a protest against elections from which their representative was allegedly barred.

A young boy is killed during clashes over land between Kapkeny and Kabasirian clans in Kerio Valley. Later reported suggest the battle caused the destructions of many homes and displaced hundreds. Fighting also spilled over into Shaban and Kachesoom areas.
Teachers in Garissa protested over deteriorating education standards in Northeastern.
Mandera residents held a demonstration to press the government into deploying teachers to the region.
Police forces foil a planned terror attack from al Shabaab. Two arrested made, weapons recovered.
A suspected cattle thief is lynched by a mob at Archers Post location.
Farmers in North Rift on 24/08 held a peaceful demonstration on the Iten-Eldoret road, Eldoret to protest over the planned introduction of genetically modified crops.
Boda boda motorcyclists in Limuru town protested after one of them was ordered to pay a bond after the individual is accused of a crime. The protesters lit fires and were later dispersed by police.
Election violence among the ODM caused two deaths, one in Awendo and the other in Rongo.
Election violence among the ODM caused two deaths, one in Awendo and the other in Rongo.
Residents of Muranga county blocked MCAs from entering the assembly in Muranga to table an impeachment motion against a preferred politician.

Nyeri residents protest, forcibly entering the officer of the governor and lighting fires in solidarity with striking nurses. The protesters called on the governor to help end the weeks long strike. Police engaged in "running battles" with the protesters.
A group of youths carrying "Maendeleo Chap Chap" banners attack people at a WDM rally in Kasikeu. Date unknown - source dated 03/09.

One person injured after being hit by a bullet when garment workers protested poor working conditions at the firm in Mombasa. The workers lit tyres on the road blocking flow of traffic for over two hours before order was restored by police who fired into the air.
Striking teachers protest over pay in Nairobi. The teachers had been striking for two weeks.

Kenyan police arrested three men found with a suspected homemade bomb as they entered a Nairobi shopping mall. The affiliations of those arrested are not known, though investigators are considering links to al Shabaab.
Teachers in Eldoret protest over pay, cause schools to close.
Striking teachers renew a protest over pay at Uhuru Park.
Striking Bondo subcounty teachers protest at the TSC office after a threat to dismiss several of their colleagues.
Residents of Bula Rahma village in the outskirts of Garissa town protest a water shortage in their area.
Teachers protest for pay increase in Muranga.
National Youth Service employees protest the termination of colleagues in Nairobi.
A group protests against genetic food mortification in Nairobi.
Residents lynch a suspected motorcycle thief in the Manyatta section of the city.
A group protests in Tetu against the actions of an ODM politician who had derided one they support.

Following the killing of a businessman by suspected gangsters, residents of Eldoret violently protest the violence, blocking the Eldoret-Kapsabet highway paralysing transport for hours. Police fired tear gas and rubber bullets against them, who then attempted to storm Langas Police Station in turn.
Health workers strike and protest in Kisumu over non-payment of saleries.
Students violently protest over delayed loans. Police use tear gas to disperse the group, make ten arrests.

Three pirates have been shot dead in Migingo Island by Ugandan security forces. The pirates, believed to be Tanzanian nationals, were accosted inside the lake while robbing fishermen. Three other pirates were arrested. Kenya and Uganda have both staked claim to the fish-rich island - a row that has lasted since 2002.
ODM elections in Kisumu county were aborted after violence broke out: a group of rowdy youths attacked a former education minister for unknown reason. "Scores" injured.

Maseno Universitys administration block was burnt on the night on 07/10 by student arsonists and rioters angry they were barred from campus elections after they failed to meet the election requirements. No injuries reported.
A vigilante group attacked and killed a suspected criminal in Nairobi.

The Jaramogi Oginga Odinga University of Science and Technology in Bondo has been closed indefinitely after students rioted following controversial elections. The students blocked the Kisumu-Usenge road engaging police in running battles for the better part of 09/10 and 10/10.
Residents of Kiangombe village in Thika held demonstrations to protest against land grabbing by a private developer.

The Jaramogi Oginga Odinga University of Science and Technology in Bondo has been closed indefinitely after students rioted following controversial elections. The students blocked the Kisumu-Usenge road engaging police in running battles for the better part of 09/10 and 10/10.
Residents of Kabete, Nairobi area hold a protest demonstration over poor roads. Police dispersed the group.

On 12/10 at 10:30, an INGO vehicle travelling without escort was stopped by a group of five armed men who had fired shots in their direction. The men kidnapped a non-local female Kenyan from the vehicle and fled after coming under fire by police.
A teacher is kidnapped by suspected al Shabaab in Hagadera refugee camp. The teacher was later rescued by Kenyan forces across the border into Somalia.
Boda Boda operators block a road in protest of a colleague who had died as a result of suspected police neglect.

Maseno University students run riot in protest of a fellow student who had fallen and died. Running battles reported with police, teargas and other implements used. Several injuries, one death reported.

The Mombasa Technical University has been closed indefinitely after students went on the rampage to protest increased fees and other management issues they say are hampering learning at the institution.

Pwani University students who attempted to disrupt Mashujaa Day celebrations at Karisa Maitha Grounds were driven back by police. They were demonstrating against the closure of the university due to a water shortage.
Turkana militia attack a Pokot camp in Narengmor, killing three in revenge of cattle theft.
Locals block the Mpeketoni-Lamu road in protest of pothole problems. The protest disrupted traffic for two hours.
One dead, eleven injured and property destroyed in a clash over sand harvesting in Kasikeu.
Students of Katheri Boys High School in Imenti Central, riot, destroying their school, in demand their principal be transferred over "highhandedness."
Traders in Gatundu Market protested on 26/10, accusing the county government of failing to provide security.

Residents of Kiutine in Igembe Central (Meru County) blocked roads leading to Kangeta and Maua towns in protest over conflicts with neighbouring communities. The conflict stemmed from access to local markets.
Jamhuri residents protest the allocation of public land for private development.

Two communities clashed at the border of Isiolo and Meru counties (roughly near Loloria) on 30/10 following the killing of a Borana boda boda rider. Police said members of the Borana community ganged up to steal motorcycles belonging to their Meru counterparts when they learned one of their own had died. The anger resulting in fighting between the two group, many of whom threw rocks at passing motorists. Police fired tear-gas to disperse the crowds.
Matatu operators block a car park, accusing private operators of driving without licences.

Matatu operators block Langata Road in protest of alleged police harassment. Police later contained the situation and towed away three minibuses n parked on the road by the protesting crew. No arrests reported.
Youths protest leadership corruption at the offices of the EACC on 10/11.
Al Shabaab kidnaps a teacher at a refugee camp Hagadera. The victim was rescued four days later.
Three bodies with bullet wounds were found in Tagwa Forest, Kieni East sub county, Nyeri county. Perpetrators, motive and time of attack not known.

A member of al Shabaab escape police, takes the officers weapon and fires several shots. Hundreds of officers cordoned off the area and engaged the suspect in a shootout until he ran out of bullets and was arrested. The suspect was injured.
Hundreds of traders took to the streets on the morning of 19/11 protesting the demolition of kiosks in Ruiru. The protesters lit fires and disrupted traffic along a highway.
Ethiopian-OLF forces and Kenyan police clash in Sololo on 19/11, three police dead. The clash began following an OLF invasion in the area.
Maasai Mara University students protest poor water services at the university by blocking a road and lighting fires. Six injuries reported.

According to a government announcement, al Shabaab have "infiltrated" the north eastern towns of Garissa, Wajir and Medina. No reported violence, though the government warns of planned attacks. Date(s) of activity not reported, source dated 21/11.
Residents of Isibania protest against the delayed construction of a road. Protesters lit a bonfires and urged Governor Okoth Obado to intervene. Business in the town "came to a halt."
A soldier was killed and six others injured in the border town of Hulugho after an Al Shabaab IED detonated. Al Shabaab, in taking credit, claims eight dead.
Al Shabaab overtakes Bula Golol in Garissa Country without resistance, then begins preaching to the residents. Military forces had fled the area prior to the al Shabaab arrival.
Residents of Nayeni, Kilifi county, held a peaceful demo in Malindi town, protesting against the grabbing of 230 acres by the government and private developers.
Al Shabaab lays siege to on Wajir on 27/11, but are quickly repelled by government soldiers. No reported death or injuries.
Mombasa traders protest the demolition of their kiosks on 28/11.
Residents of Nkunga in Meru blocked a highway in protest of a spate of attack by wild animals in the region. The protesters demanded the Wildlife Service gain better control of the local wildlife.
Garissa residents protest frequent water supply problems on 30/11.
Police engage Moi University students in running battles during a violent protest over the releasing of university student records.

About 200 demonstrators held a peaceful march to the Supreme Court and Parliament buildings where they delivered petitions asking those institutions to do more to tackle corruption in Kenyan government. Police blocked the protesters from entering, fired tear gas canisters and made several arrests.
Gachie residents protest against a crime spike in their area on 03/12.
Al Shabaab attacks Kenyan forces in Lamu on 06/12, seven soldiers killed, ten wounded.
An AP police officer opens fire indiscriminately on people in Hulugho on 06/12, injuring one. Authorities are attempting to ascertain if the attack was al Shabaab related.
Widows protest in Keringet over government neglect.
Suspected al Shabaab ambush a group of soldiers in (or near) Mandera on 13/12, killing one and wounding two others.
A Senator leads a protest over "land-grabbing" in a Nairobi area.

A roadside bomb or landmine, suspected to have origin with al Shabaab, detonates in Mandara, targeting and killing a group of five (later determined to be seven) police officers. The landmine was planted inside the customs and border compound. The attack come a day after an ambush on a group of soldiers in the town.
Protestors, drawn from various WTO member countries, staged a protest outside a Nairobi conference over development delays.
Two are killed during a gun battle between al Shabaab and security forces in Milihoi.
A threat is announced and a bomb later discovered in a Catholic church in Kutu. Its discovery caused congregants to panic and flee. Police later detonated the explosive without injury.
Al Shabaab attacks and kills three police officers outside Mandera on 21/12. The attack may have been coordinated or related to an attack on bus travellers in the area.
Al Shabaab attacks and kills bus two travellers and wounds three others south of Mandera between Kotulo and Daba (Another report indicate the attacks occurred near El Wak) in Mandera County on 21/12.
One dead and several injured following a border attack between two villages in Kisumu county on 22/12.
Two headers are killed in violence between Kalenjin and Maasais in Maasai Mau Narok forest, Narok South Sub-County on 23/12.
Four police officers are feared dead following an al Shabaab attack on Bodhei, Lamu County on 25/12.

Many houses are destroyed, causing 2,000 residents to flee following renewed violence between Kalenjins and Maasais groups in the Olposimoru area of Narok on 25/12. Causalities, injuries from the clash are not known.

A member of al Shabaab, attempting to plant a roadside bomb, dies when the device exploded prematurely. The perpetrator was believed to be hurried when he saw that the police had noticed his activities and attempted top stop him. A matter of dispute, the Daily Nation reported police had killed the perpetrator, followed by the explosion.
Four are injured in continued clashes between Kalenjin and Maasais groups on 26/12 in the Olposimoru area of Narok.
Two suspected thieves are lynched in Ndithini on 26/12.
Two police are attacked on 27/12 along the Lafey-Elwak road, Mandera county. Two others reported dead as well. No immediate claim of responsibility, though al Shabaab are suspected.
Three are killed in renewed clashes between Kalenjin and Maasais groups in the Olposimoru area of Narok on 27/12.

Three people were killed and two others injured after an explosion went off in a vehicle within Mandera town on 28/12. Al Shabaab suspected. The explosion caused a group of locals to hold a demonstration against military forces, mistakenly believing members of the military had been responsible for the deaths of the civilians.

Police clash with a group of matatu operators in the northern suburbs of Mombasa, fifteen injuries reported. The officers were chasing a matatu that had defied orders to stop at the Kenol stage on the Mombasa-Malindi highway near City Mall.

Three people were killed and two others injured after an explosion went off in a vehicle within Mandera town on 28/12. Al Shabaab suspected. The explosion caused a group of locals to hold a demonstration against military forces, mistakenly believing members of the military had been responsible for the deaths of the civilians.
Vigilantes lynch four suspected cattle thieves in Nyakach on 29/12.
A pair of thieves are attacked and nearly lynched before they are rescued.

Suspected al Shabaab ambushed a police convoy in Lamu on the afternoon of 01/01, injuring security officials and setting a police truck on fire. There was a fierce gun battle at the scene preceded by an explosion. Shortly after the attack police forces in the area launched a large security operation.

Five men were admitted to hospital after they were attacked by a gang of armed men in Silaloni, Samburu Sub-County, in Kwale. The camel keepers were attacked by men armed with pangas, bows and arrows as well as other crude weapons on the morning of 02/01. The reason for attack is not known.
Hundreds of women on 10/01 protested in Mombasa against a Senator who publically criticised President Uhuru Kenyatta. The protesters demanded the Senator apologise.
The Anti-Terrorism Police Unit on [20 January] morning killed four al Shabaab after a shootout in Kwachocha, Malindi.
Laikipia University students riot following a released report recommending the closure of their school. Police fired tear gas and made several arrests.

Three people were killed while another one was seriously injured after morans from two communities clashed over land in Leparua on the Isiolo-Laikipia border. The identity of the actors are not known.
Six police (or seven - Shabelle Media Network) officers are killed when their vehicle struck an IED in Lamu, suspected al Shabaab responsible.
More than 400 residents of Mpeketoni in Lamu County protested over increased insecurity and frequent attacks by Al-Shabaab militia which have been experienced in the region in the recent past.
Al Shabaab attacks Pandanguo village, targeting the homes of Christians. Al Shabaab claimed "many" killed, though more reliable reports indicate three dead, plus injuries.
A gang on the night of 31/01 raided Meru Governor Peter Munyas home and vandalised one of his official security cars. The governor was away, and was not harmed.
Suspected Tugen militia attack and kill a Njemp (Ilchamus) man in Olesampurmpur Village in Baringo 31/01.
Residents engage in running battles with the police after the city confiscated a car wash machine from a business. No reported injury.
Security forces kill four members of al Shabaab and recover weapons in Boni Forest on 02/02.
Following an attack on a Njemp man by Tuden militia, Njemp men seek revenge and kill three Tuden people in Mbechot Village of Baringo on 02/02.
Residents of Ndagani protest the poor state of a road on 03/02, burning tyres.
Taxi drivers violently protest the advent of Uber in the city. The drivers believe the ride sharing service will upset their business.

Chuka University students violently protest disputed school elections by looting shops and lighting fires. Police made 15 arrests and offices temporarily closed the university. The date(s) of the protest are not known. The election was held on 29/01, though it is not clear if protests immediately followed.
A vigilante group attacks and kills a man they suspect of murder in Eastleigh.

Cooperative farmers in Naivasha burn several houses in protest over "malpractice" of land division. Police fired into the air to disperse the group. Earlier, the demonstrators had forced four primary schools and a secondary school to close down, with students joining them in the day-long demonstrations.

Rioters block traffic at Olololunga, between Narok and Bomet after a motorist killed a number of cattle while speeding along the roadway. Anti-riot police came to the scene to "contain the situation," though it is not clear if the police engaged the protesters.
Militias from Maasai and Kalenjin clash over land at Kosovo in Naivasha (Mathare). Six houses destroyed, 1 killed and 1 injured.
Kikuyu and Luo ethnic communities clash in Kariobangi suburb over voter registration. One death reported.

A decision by the Narok County Government to close 15 camps in the Maasai Mara Game Reserve has sparked protests on 02/03 from the local community, mostly from tour operators and hoteliers who benefit from the tourism industry.
Supporters of KANU and police clash at the Moi Gardens location after police attempted to stop a political rally when the event space had been booked by another group.

Jomo Kenyatta University of Agriculture and Technology (JKUAT) students took to the streets in riot on 09/03 over the death of a student at the institution, for whom they blame a local hospital for negligence.

A group of Ethiopian nationals are attacked and nearly lynched in a Nairobi suburb by a vigilante mob who blame them for a recent murder of boda driver. The police were able to intervene before any bloodshed.
Hundreds of women in Malindi staged a demonstration following an assault of a person during the recent parliamentary by-election.

Four members of a vigilante mob are shot and wounded when police opened fire on the group who were attempting to lynch a suspected thief. The vigilantes had chased the suspect into a house when the police opened fire to disperse them. One police officer was also reported injured.
Mombasa residents gather to protest a county plan to demolish old houses in their area.
The Students Organisation of Nairobi University (SONU) chairman Babu Owino is charged with severely assaulting a fellow student during the height of the student elections.
After a murder suspect is released by police he is attacked and killed by vigilantes in suburban Nairobi.
Residents of Kirimon in Samburu Central Sub-County protest over what they say is illegal grabbing of 10,000 acres of public land meant to benefit their community.

Following several high-speed automobile accidents in their area, residents of Mairo Inya erect several speed bumps on a thoroughfare. Following their action, a group of motorists stage a protest of the poor driving condition.

Members of the Akorino religious sect protest at 47 churches throughout Embu county over alleged discrimination after their children were sent home from school after refusing to remove their headgear.
A vigilante mob lynches and burns a suspected thief in Mariani on 29/03.
Police use tear-gas to disperse a group of "rowdy" matatu operators who blocked roads in downtown Nairobi ahead of a planned strike to protest parking license cancellation.
Residents of Kirinyaga County protest a law that would move the countys headquarters. Date of protest not known - source dated 04/04.

University of Nairobi students protest a dispute in a campus union poll, burn the Students Organisation of Nairobi University (Sonu) offices and block a section of University Way and Uhuru Highway before police used teargas to disperse them. The protest caused the school to temporally close.

Residents of Ndoto Ward in Samburu North Sub County on 05/04 held protests at Lesirkan trading centre over the recent police recruitment exercise which they claimed was unfair and marred with corruption.
Al Shabaab fighters attack a police station in Dif on 10/04, injuring three officers before escaping in the police vehicle.
Laikipia University students block roads to protest examination fees, causing the school to close.
Masinde Muliro University students protest examination fees, causing the school to temporarily close. No reported violence.
Students of Masinde Muliro University protest exam fees on 12/04.

Tens of business owners in Embu Town Wednesday (13/04) afternoon held a peaceful demonstration protesting alleged harassment by Kenya Bureau of Standards (Kebs) officials. [The demonstrators] marched to the Embu County government and county commissioners offices seeking to be addressed but were repulsed by police. Kebs officials had accused many of the traders of selling counterfeit items and threatened them with arrest.
After a man drowns residents of Miangeni block a road in protest of government neglect.
Protesters burn the home of a Embu man suspected of child rape after he is released on bond.
Police tear-gas electorial reform protesters in Nairobi. Warning shots and tear gas was firied after the protest broke a police line.

Protesting members of CORD are tear-gassed by police after they attempt to forcibly enter the offices of the electorial comission in Kisumu. CORD was attempting to "kick out" the commissions officials.
Police officers in Kasarani lobbed teargas to disperse hundreds of boda boda riders who had barricaded the Thika Superhighway at Roysambu, Kamiti protesting the death of a colleague.

A group of residents in Emurua Dikirr Constituency protest outside the Ward Administrators office over the poor state of the roads which led to a number of local deaths. Another group launches a counter protest at the same location and accuses the demonstrators of illegal protest and undermining the county leadership. There is no reports of violence between the two groups.
Businessman and prominent critic of the government Jacob Juma is shot dead by unknown gunmen in Nairobi. Nothing was stolen. The opposition has labelled his killing an assassination.

Police disperse "opposition protesters" at the offices of the electoral commission in Nairobi due to alleged bias and corruption. Police involvement began after many of the protesters began pelting the officers with stones.

In Kwale, a group of opposition CORD supporters made their way to the IEBC offices in Diani, Msambweni Sub-County, peacefully handed a letter to the assistant returning officer Mwamize Achani and left. Source dated 10/05.
A CORD protest in Kisumu is met with "heavy police presence." No reported violence. Exact date not known - source dated 10/05.
Four people were shot and killed while one person is missing as renewed inter-clan fighting erupted at Kachamcham farm, Kerio Valley in Elgeyo-Marakwet County.
Residents attack and kill a suspected robber in Buruburu on 15/04.

CORD protesters clash with police in Kisii on 16/05. The demos, which started from Kisii Hotel, turned chaotic when the protestors attempted to force their way into the IEBC offices. Fifteen arrested.
Police use tear gas and clash electoral commission protesters during a protest in Nairobi. Reports of excessive violence reported from police. Fifteen arrests reported.

Several ODM supporters in Kisumu sustained injures after police broke up a weekly demonstration to eject Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission officers. It is not known if the violence against the protesters was blatant or intentional. No violence reported from the protesters.
A group of women lynched a man who was suspected to have stabbed his wife to death.
Violence at Karatina market in Nyeri after rival camps of supporters of area governor and an MP (both of the Jubilee Coalition) clashed at a ceremony.
Police clash with electoral commission protesters in Kakamega on 23/05. Injuries not known.
Police used tear gas to disperse CORD protesters in the Kibera slum of Nairobi. Demonstrators responded by throwing stones.
Five people were shot by prison warders in Migori County during violent electoral commission demonstrations.

CORD protesters demonstrate against the electoral commission in Mombasa. The protesters were dispersed with police tear gas following running battles between the two groups. Sixteen arrests, including the Mombasa County Assembly Speaker.
CORD protesters attempt to gather at the capital to protest against the electoral commission but are quickly dispersed by police tear gas after the group blocked a road.

Three people died during clashes which erupted during opposition protests against actions of the electoral commission in two towns. Two people died of gunshot wounds and 25 wounded in the western town of Siaya, and one from a head injury after falling over while running from tear gas in Kisumu. Police in Siaya opened fire "in self defence" after "a mob with catapults" approached a municipal office. Twenty-nine police injured in the clash. The actions of the demonstrators in Kisumu are not clear.
CORD members protest in Homa Bay, marching toward county election commission offices. Police intervene, 6 protesters were wounded. It is not known if the protesters were violent.

Three people died during clashes which erupted during opposition protests against actions of the electoral commission in two towns. Two people died of gunshot wounds in the western town of Siaya, and one from a head injury after falling over while running from tear gas in Kisumu. Police in Siaya opened fire "in self defence" after "a mob with catapults" approached a municipal office. Twenty-nine police injured in the clash. The actions of the demonstrators in Kisumu are not clear and may have been attacked without provocation.

Forty-five members of al Shabaab are witnessed crossing into Kenya at Sugrow, Wajir County. One group of 13 was sighted headed towards Gerille, another towards Konton and another towards Gumarey areas of Wajir East.

Three Nyumba Kumi officials were assassinated by gunmen in Diani, Kwale County [coast region] on Sunday [29 May]. The perpetrators are believed to be al Shabaab. The three were killed separately, each in their homes.

Students of St Pauls Kiwanjani Mixed Secondary School in Isiolo went on strike the morning of 31/05, destroying and stealing property. The students destroyed classroom window panes and looted electronics, computers, books and teachers laptops before police intervened. The violence was sparked after several students were suspended for drug use.

Armed men believed to be members of Al-Shabaab have killed three people in Kwale in Kenyas coastal region. The Kenyan government said the people killed were elders. Reports say that masked armed men arrived at the coastal town and hounded the people out of their homes and killed them in an open field.
Police officers protest over unpaid salaries.

A convoy transporting Kenyan defence forces (KDF) was targeted in a roadside bomb explosion outside Liboi town near Somali border by suspected al Shabaab. The bomb blast has destroyed one of vehicles in the convoy, causing unidentified casualties as Kenyan military did not comment on the IED attack.
A group of students attack and kill a man at Abubakar Integrated Schools mosque in Tsunguli Village in Matuga Sub-County, Kwale County over allegations of witchcraft.
CORD protests in Migori during the later evening hours. The protest became violent the following day.
Transport along the Kisumu-Kakamega highway was (06/06) morning paralysed after youths who are protesting against the electoral commission blocked the road at Kibuye.
CORD protesters from Mathare threw stones at vehicles, forcing motorists to use alternative routes.
CORD youths blocked all major roads in Migori Town and lit bonfires in protests against the Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission (IEBC). The protest began the following evening.
Truck drivers block roads in protest of police harassment and insecurity on 06/06.
CORD youths protest in Kibera.

CORD youths blocked roads, lit fires and looted businesses in Kisumu in protest of electoral commission on 06/06. Two deaths reported, plus 26 other injuries. Security officers watched the protests from a distance, though it was later reported police were responsible for the two dead. Human Rights watch reports the police opened fire into a peaceful crowd.
Jubilee supporters in Eldoret held a peaceful demonstration and condemned intra party political remarks that appeared to go against a pact between coalition affiliates TNA and URP.

Jubilee Coalition supporters carrying banners stormed into the Donnies Hotel, where [Coalition for Reforms and Democracy] was holding a meeting with different leaders. They demanded that the leader of CRD leave the county. Police dispersed the protesters.

An IED detonated at Mandera, near the Somali border on 11/06. No causalities reported. The Mandera County Commissioner said the incident, which took place at Border Point Three area near custom offices, had targeted security officers manning the border area and was likely caused by al Shabaab.
Students of Lamu Bujra Boys High School go on a violent protest after several other students were suspended over a disciplinary matter.

Protest in a Nairobi slum after footage appearing to show a pro-government legislator saying top opposition leader Raila Odinga can be assassinated appeared. Police fired tear-gas, protesters responded with throwing stones.
Unidentified gunmen shoot and kill an area chief in Kiambu during the evening hours.

On 15/06 CORD protests broke out in "western Kenya" following the arrest of opposition leaders for hate speech allegations. The source implies the location was a reference to either Kisumu or Siaya county.
Eight Kenyans have been kidnapped by the al-Shabab militants in the past month in the Alango and Kurokura (Mandera County) areas. Dates unknown, though the latest kidnapping took place on 10/07.
Two are dead in or near Kopere trading centre over a land control issue. Violence related to the land continued in the general area midweek.
Police open fire on "mostly peaceful" CORD protesters in "Nyanza region", killing five "since Monday" (source dated 22/06).
Five Kenyan policemen escorting a passenger bus have been killed after al-Shabaab fighters ambushed their convoy in El Wak on 20/06. Al Shabaab later claimed responsibility for the attack.
Anti-terrorism police on 20/06 thwarted an attack and killed a wanted al-Shabaab fighter in the coastal town of Kwale.
One dead and three injured when an ambulance hit a suspected al-Shabaab planted land mine in Hulugho.
At least 300 tuberculosis (TB) and HIV/Aids patients in Isiolo protested against plans to convert a regional TB isolation centre into county assembly offices.
More than 200 residents on 21/06 staged a peaceful demonstration over what they termed as neglect by the county government.
Police open fire on "mostly peaceful" CORD protesters in "Nyanza region", killing five "since Monday" (source dated 22/06).
Police open fire on "mostly peaceful" CORD protesters in "Nyanza region", killing five "since Monday" (source dated 22/06).
A widow and a middle aged man were shot with arrows at Daraja Mbili and Songhor areas over a land issue. The attack is a carry over of hostilities which began on 18/06.
A widow and a middle aged man were shot with arrows at Daraja Mbili and Songhor areas over a land issue. The attack is a carry over of hostilities which began on 18/06.
Al Shabaab are reported to have struck Damasa border town and destroyed a Safaricom communication mast and a water pump using explosives. No reported human causality or violence.
Students of Itierio Boys High School in Kisii burnt down seven of their 12 dormitories after their teachers refused to allow them to watch a football match on television.
Kenyan forces kill four members of al Shabaab in Milimani and recover weapons.
Al Shabaab claims it has killed 6 KDF soldiers in an ambush attack on a base of Kenyan troops in Lamu Island near Somalia border. KDF denies either the attack took place or the causality figure.

Six people were killed and scores injured when a bus plying the Mandera-Nairobi route was sprayed with bullets by heavily armed assailants between Wargadud and Elwak. Government sources believe the assailants may have been a local militia group, not al Shabaab, which was the initial suspicion.

A group protests in Uhuru Park following the murder of a lawyer. The source claims protests were also took place in "major towns and urban centres countrywide," though did not make any specific names or instances.

Parents and members of Christians of Lutheran Church hold a demonstration on July 4, 2016 opposing a move by the Teachers Service Commission to sack principals in whose schools there were burning of dormitories at Boys High School in Kisii.
Al Shabaab attacks and kills a civilian in their home in Mbuwani.
Protests in Eldoret following reported domestic violence in the area.
Protesters burned a police camp during a protest recent against extra-judicial killings linked to police.
Suspected [al Shabaab] was on Wednesday morning shot dead by police in Kibundani, Msambweni Sub County.
Police shoot and kill a al Shabaab suspect in Kwale town.

More than 100 Al Shabaab raided Diff Police station in Wajir on early Saturday morning, stealing firearms and bullets. They left one police officer wounded, and are believed to have escaped with serious injuries during an exchange of fire with officers during the 1 am incident. Al Shabaab gained control of the town after several hours of fighting. The Somali Memo reports causalities without number.
A woman was killed while three others were critically injured when suspected Al-Shabaab gunmen attacked a vehicle between Fino and Lafey at around 7pm on Saturday night.
Police officers, on their way to Lamu, escaped death by a whisker after al Shabaab militia men attempted to attack their vehicle which was heading to Mokowe in Lamu County on Sunday.

Military forces foil an ambush on a convoy in Lamu by identifying IEDs and detonating them. No injuries. The security forces are reportedly in pursuit of the suspected attackers in the area. The planned attack and subsequent security sweep took place on 12/07.

Six people were injured in a confrontation between ODM and Jubilee supporters in Mumias East constituency on Tuesday evening. The violence erupted after alleged supporters of the Orange Democratic Movement (ODM) allegedly defaced Jubilee party campaign messages and paintings on rocks on the Kakamega-Mumias road.

A man was shot dead while another injured on Wednesday night when gunmen laid an ambush at Pimbinyiet at the border of Trans Mara East and Trans Mara West Sub-Counties. The identities of the attackers as well as their motive is unknown.

A suspected [al Shabaab] held at a police station in western Kenya grabbed a gun and shot at police officers, killing between six, leading to a hostage situation. Despite initial reports, the police force later revealed the shooter was likely a disgruntled police officer.
An al-Shabaab suspect was killed in Kenyas coastal town of Lamu in a foiled dawn attack at a local police station. One officer was injured.
Following the arrest of their colleagues, boda boda operators storm a police station in Likoni and clash with police. Injuries not known.
Police raid a al Shabaab hideout, kill two suspects.

A journalist was seriously beaten and injured during [opposition] Cord [Coalition for Reforms and Democracy] leader Raila Odingas rally in Port Victoria, Budalangi constituency [western Kenya]. The journalist survived after police intervened.
Following the death of a man in a road accident area residents protest the errant driver.
Man found killed, throat slit and body dumped in rice farm in Thiba. Perpetrators not known but locals blame terror gangs.
A KDF convoy runs over a al Shabaab-planted landmine in Ishakani, five injured.
Coffee farmers cut down trees in protest of pay in Mukurwe-ini "early this week."

A Kenya Defence Forces (KDF) convoy was ambushed after their vehicle overran an explosive in Fino Town, Mandera County. Between 6 and 10 causalities. Elsewhere in Fino on the same date Al Shabaab destroys a communication mast in Fino and engage police in a gunfight. Four injuries.
Youths protest after Chinese nationals had been contracted to build a railway rather than locals.
Suspected al Shabaab detonate an explosive at a police building injuring one officer.

Youths, wielding weapons, attacked a group of Chinese workers contracted to build a railway in Duka Moja, Narok County. The attack is related to a protest the previous day in which the group had demanded locals be hired by labourers. Injuries reported.

Three people were shot dead [3 August] while five others were seriously injured when police officers fired on a mob that had forced their way into Bondo police station to lynch two women alleged to have stolen a baby.
A vigilante mob beat a woman to death who they suspect of witchcraft near Kilifi.
Sand transporters have blocked Mombasa Road in Makueni County in protest of harassment from local government officials. The protesters caused traffic problems, but did not cause injury.

More than 20 houses were on Sunday night set ablaze by arsonists in Pimbinyiet sub-location, Narok County, escalating tension between members of two neighbouring communities following the murder of a man the previous day. Injuries not known.
Four police officers were injured during an attack by suspected Al-Shabaab militants who tried to force their way into the Basuba General Service Unit (GSU) camp in Lamu East on Saturday evening.
Tea farmers protest poor current market price of their product at Kiangai market.
A man from Pimbinyiet sub location is discovered murdered by suspected rival-neighbours.

More than 50 casual employees at Menengai Oil Refineries in Nakuru claim they have not been paid their salaries and they are subjected to poor working conditions. The aggrieved workers on Wednesday evening downed their tools and held a demonstration demanding settlement of their salary arrears.

Police have gunned down a al Shabaab terror suspect and recovered two hand grenades in Vingirika (Diani) village, Kwale County. The suspect Mohamed Bakari was shot dead by Anti-terrorism detectives after he hauled a hand grenade at the officers.

SOURCE: KBC Online text website, Nairobi, in English 14 Aug 16
NOTES: Police kill two al Shabaab suspects during a gunbattle in the Kisauni area of Mombasa.
One is dead following a fight between two rival communities Kuri, Isiolo County on 14/08.
Residents of Kiriko Village in Tetu, Nyeri County Sunday night lynched an armed robber after an attempted robbery as police recovered a pistol.
Police clash with market traders in Isiolo. Three injured, including a police officer.
Riots have rocked Mitaboni, Machakos County following the killing of five guards in a recent gang attack.
Road workers in Ichuni Ward, Kisii County protest over delayed pay.
A mob lynches a man suspected of child abuse.
Political rivals clash at a church meeting. Injuries not known.

Dozens of residents of Njoguini in Nyeri County Tuesday staged a protest in Naro Moru Township demanding a stop to a Sh35 million dam project. The residents expressed dissatisfaction with the location of the dam saying it is being built downstream instead of upstream.
Hundreds of farmers demonstrated at Thumaita Tea Factory in Kirinyaga to protest over poor bonus payment.

A Muslim cleric died on Saturday evening after his vehicle hit an improvised explosive device (IED) in the Kenyan coastal county of Lamu, near the border with Somalia. Al Shabaab are the suspected perpetrators.
Three houses were Tuesday set ablaze as hundreds of rioting tea farmers continued wreaking havoc in Kirinyaga County in protests over what they say is poor bonus payment.
Nurses strike, protest in Migori over payment of arrears.
Parents of Kimuchu Secondary School in Thika paralysed learning on the first day of term in protest over what they termed as exorbitant charges.

Students from St Pauls Kevote High School in Embu County on Thursday held a peaceful demonstration over the transfer of their principal Mr Paul Muriuki to Nkubu High School. During the protest the students walked from their school to nearby Embu.
A section of Rui-Ruiru coffee farmers in Kiamariga staged a protest over poor payment rates and alleged embezzlement of funds by the management.
Tea farmers protest over pay in Tombe.
Tea farmers protest over pay in Gianchore.
Students protest over the transfer of their teacher.
Journalists protest in several cities following the mysterious death (attributed to thugs) of a colleague.
Journalists protest in several cities following the mysterious death (attributed to thugs) of a colleague.
Miraa farmers and traders in Nyambene, Meru County (near Meru Town) took to the streets protesting the recent ban on Kenyan khat planes to Somalia.
Journalists protest in several cities following the mysterious death (attributed to thugs) of a colleague.
Journalists protest in several cities following the mysterious death (attributed to thugs) of a colleague.
Journalists protest in several cities following the mysterious death (attributed to thugs) of a colleague.
A Borana man is attacked and killed by Somali herders in Garfasa, Isiolo County. The attack is believed to be retaliatory.

Al Shabaab claimed responsibility for double roadside explosions targeted Kenyan defence forces near the town of Mandera on 09/09. Pro-al shabaab media outlets, citing unnamed commander reported that at least 4 Kenyan army soldiers died in the IED blasts on the KDF military convoy.

At least four more people have been killed in raging armed conflict between Borana and Somali herders (Auliyan) along the Isiolo-Garissa border [northeastern Kenya]. The fighting took place in Tana village about 11km north of Garba-Tula town on Saturday [10 September].

A group of three women (later learned to had pledged allegiance to Islamic State) attack a police station in Mombasa. The three entered the police station on 11/09 under the guise to report a stolen phone. One drew a knife, the second threw an explosive and the third attempted to detonate a dud suicide pack. The officers responded and killed the three. Two police injured. A fourth suspect was arrested in the following days.
High school students riot after they are denied a social event with a nearby girls school.
Ethnic clash over rights of a watering hole near Molot. Several houses were burnt in the melee.
Students of Siakago Boys High School in Embu County went on the rampage Tuesday night, protesting the shaming of their colleagues who were earlier in the day found swimming in a river.
Residents protest recent banditry in their area.
Protesters marched in Kenyas capital against plans to build an elevated railway line over the countrys oldest national park, saying it will threaten wildlife.

Two rival groups, those supportive of the Kirinyaga governor (TNA) and those supportive of a influential businesswoman clashed at the site of a marathon. Police intervened and dispersed the two groups.
A mob from Kiawara slums in Nyeri Sunday night lynched a former robbery convict after he attempted to steal from a house.
Journalists in Mombasa protest limits on free expression and other harassing behaviour.
Doctors protest over pay in Nairobi.
Al Shabaab attacks a police station in Hamey, near Garissa. The insurgents killed six officers and captured two others.
Al Shabaab, numbering 50, attacks a police station in Liboi. One of the assailants was killed and several seriously injured during a gunbattle.

Residents blocked the Mombasa-Lunga Lunga road on Friday after one person died and six others were injured in an accident involving two matatus and a truck. The residents lit bonfires and barricaded the road with stones to protest frequent crashes on the road.

Police on Tuesday used tear gas to disperse protesters in Eldoret town after they took to the streets over the summoning of two governors to record statements over utterances they made when they stormed Moi University to oppose the appointment of a new vice-chancellor. There were also protests in Iten town over the same issue.
University students, protesting the death of a colleague due to accident, engage the police in running battles near Ongata Rongai. Two students and two police officers sustained injury.

Police on Tuesday used tear gas to disperse protesters in Eldoret town after they took to the streets over the summoning of two governors to record statements over utterances they made when they stormed Moi University to oppose the appointment of a new vice-chancellor. There were also protests in Iten town over the same issue.
Police kill an al Shabaab recruiter during a shootout.
Pedestrians protest against reckless motorists.
Residents barricade a road, lighting fires in protest of a recent alleged accidental killing of a tuk tuk driver at the hands of police.
Residents protest a water shortage in Garissa.
A group of Anglicans protest in support of their Bishop who was in the process of being sued for defamation.
A cross-border al Shabaab attack kills six in Mandera. The attackers targeted "non-locals" and/or "Christians."
A man was burnt to death by a mob in Meru after he allegedly stabbed a guard to death.
Protesters blocked the busy Eldoret-Malaba highway after five guards were killed by unknown persons the previous evening. Police fired in the air to disperse the protesters.
A farmer is attacked and killed over land in the Kosovo area of Naivasha.
Students riot after their examination results are posted publically.
Contractors protest delayed payments at the county offices on Hola over several days.
Isiolo County staff protest a work stoppage.
Contractors protest delayed payments at the county offices on Hola over several days.
Hundreds of residents of Karatina in Nyeri County took to the streets to protest a two-day water shortage that has hit the town.
Contractors protest delayed payments at the county offices on Hola over several days.
Victims of a bank heist protest.
Contractors protest delayed payments at the county offices on Hola over several days.
Elders protested a meeting at Chuka University on Saturday, accusing a patron of favouritism.
Police use tear gas to disperse an ongoing contactors protest when they had become "rowdy."
Kisii University students burned a section of the administration block in protest over an order to clear school fees by Monday or postpone their studies.
A night guard was on Monday night killed by a stray bullet during a shootout between police and suspected al Shabaab gunmen in Mandera. One death reported.
A widow was beheaded by a vigilante mob in Samogara Village, Kisii County over allegations of witchcraft.

Al Shabaab gunmen detonated explosives at Boshari Guesthouse during the early morning hours. Twelve killed, others injured. Al Shabaab claimed responsibility, saying the targets of their attacks were Christians. Police later imposed a dusk till dawn curfew.
Two children sustained gunshot injuries on Tuesday night when a lone gunman attacked the home of ODM candidate Josphat Ekeno ahead of a by-election.

Near violence at Mochengo polling centre in Nyacheki on Wednesday after a member of Kisii County Assembly (Jubilee Party) opened fire to disperse a group of "rowdy" ODM youths who where attempting to attack him over bribery concerns.
A man was shot and killed by Kenyan police outside the US embassy in the capital Nairobi on Thursday after stabbing an officer with a knife. IS later claimed responsibility.
Residents of Muranga protest after the local county bought land below market price. The demonstrators attempted to enter county officers, but were dispersed by police.
A prisoner released on Presidential pardon is lynched in Salawa.
University of Maseno students attack and kill a man they believed murdered a colleague.
Students of Nyabururu Girls High School in Kisii County are protesting the interdiction of their principal after reports of abuse.
A group of activists protested, calling for the resignation of Health Principal Secretary over accusations of graft.
Police disperse an anti-corruption protest with tear gas.
Residents of Uruku in Meru on Saturday held demonstrations outside Uruku police post protesting the death of a suspect in one of the cells.
Jubilee supporters protest at the appointment by the Deputy President. Police made arrests.
One person has died while eight others have been injured in morning clashes between the Kisii and Kipsigis groups at Olmelil along the Narok-Kisii border.
Six people died and two others were injured in fighting between Jibril and Matan clans in Wajir county [in northeast Kenya] on Saturday.
Bomet Governor Isaac Rutos Chama cha Mashinani supporters clashed with those of Jubilee Party at Silbwet Stadium forcing police to tear gas them to quell the situation.

Bahati residents blocked the Nakuru-Nyahururu road disrupting transport activities for over three hours on Wednesday after the county government allegedly failed to help in retrieving a body of a boy from a dam.
Taxi operators protest competition from Uber in Nairobi.
A man was shot dead and two other people injured as police battled a villagers protesting the killing of two guards.
A vigilante group lynches a suspected murderer at Nthangarine, in Meru County.
Dozens of students from Kisii Universitys Eldama Ravine campus demonstrated against the closure of the university.
Al Shabaab enters two villages in Ijara sub-county, forcing residents to hear a lecture in their local mosque.

Police lobbed teargas canisters and shot in the air to disperse a group of youths allied to Governor Mwangi wa Iria. The youths attempted to storm Mumbi grounds which has been booked by Kigumo MP Jamleck Kamau. During the protest the demonstrators sang anti-Kamau songs.
Four Al-Shabaab members were killed in El-Wak, Mandera County after a combined team of security officers thwarted a planned terror attack against specific high value targets including police camps.
A clash between Jimo and Agoro clans lasts over two days. One death reported the first day, two the second.
A clash between Jimo and Agoro clans lasts over two days. One death reported the first day, two the second.

Unidentified gunmen open fire on a group of students sitting for examination in Wajir. The gunmen later exchanged fire with police with were guarding the institution. Motive not known. No reported deaths.
Al Shabaab attacked Haluqa, outside of Garissa, targeting a Safaricom building. The attackers abducted several workers and took them into Somalia.

Unidentified gunmen open fire on a group of students sitting for examination in Wajir. The gunmen later exchanged fire with police with were guarding the institution. Motive not known. No reported deaths.
Traders protest forced eviction in Isiolo.
Workers of a tea company strike and protest over pay.
Suspected al Shabaab target police with an IED in Mandera. No causalities.
The day after a group of armed robbers shot and killed a teacher, residents of Isebania border town block roads in protest.

Residents of Kathwana in Tharaka-Nithi demonstrated over a statement made by the Deputy President which appeared to suggest the national government does not recognise the town as the countys headquarters.
Offices of the Vihiga County government are destroyed by unidentified arsonists.

Three people are injured in Mandera after their fuel tanker ran over an Improvised Explosive Device (IED) between Kotulo and Chuma Mrefu. Al Shabaab suspected. A similar attack against police occurred earlier in the week.

Residents of Mercy Njeri area of Nakuru county on the evening of 03/12 evening blocked the Nakuru- Kabarak road as they protested the killing of two brothers by a police officer (details of incident not clear.)
A military patrol encounters and kill four suspected members of al Shabaab in the Hulugho area on 09/12.
Residents "recently" protest the high number of traffic accidents in the area.
Police arrest three and use tear gas during an anti-government corruption protest in Kenya. No violence reported from the protesters.

Suspected Al-Shabaab have attacked Dabacity in Elwak, Mandera County and destroyed a Safaricom telecommunication mast. County Commissioner Fredrick Shisia said the attack occurred at about 1.45am on 12/12.The attackers overpowered five security operatives guarding the mast, causing them to flee.
Three journalists were reported assaulted by "county officials" at Nyakongo school, Nyamira County.
Migori government workers strike and protest over pay.
Military forces kill four members of al Shabaab in Hulugho during the mid-morning of 15/12.
Nurses at the Nyeri County Referral Hospital have on 16/12 held a peaceful demonstration protesting over delayed payments and promotions.

Former Kitui mayor was crushed to death and a former Land minister was injured after protests against the demolition of kiosks turned riotous in Kitui town. Following the incident, the driver of the truck defended himself, claiming the protesters threated to lynch him and burn the truck.
Members of the Kabsiren clan attacked and killed two of their Kapshoi counterparts accusing them of "harbouring their enemies" from the Pokot community.

Pokot raiders attack and kill a crossing guard during in Liter village and two others in neighbouring Endo Location, both in the Kerio valley the early morning hours. The attacks led to ethnic tension in the area.
More than 600 demonstrators from Sagalla in Taita Taveta County on 20/12 blocked the Nairobi-Mombasa highway to protest against increased cases of human-wildlife conflict in the area.
Members of a Kipsigs militia attack and kill two Maasai in retaliation for earlier violence.
A Kipsigis is killed by people believed to be from the Maasai community outside Kilgoris at Esoit trading centre. The attack led to retaliation from Kipsigs militia.

Three people were on 21/12 are killed in Esoit, Trans Mara West (outside Kilgoris) in Narok County as fighting between the Kipsigis and Maasai communities. The fighting was an escalation of tit-for-tat attacks the previous day.
Lawmakers from major opposition parties in Kenya staged a walkout from a parliamentary session to protest the passage of a contentious legal provision.

One attacker died and three police officers were wounded Friday after a group of men armed with machetes and bows assaulted a coastal police post to steal guns, an official said. No group has claimed responsibility, but initial suspicion has fallen on a secessionist group called the Mombasa Republican Council that wants the coastal region to secede from Kenya, claiming marginalization.
At least two people were killed and some others injured by suspected al-Shabaab who vandalized a communication mast in the Tarbaj area near the border with Somalia.

One person was killed on the night of 26/12 while three others sustained serious injuries following an attack by suspected Pokot militia in Kerio Valley. A similar attack occurred earlier in the week.
A Kipsigis man is dead and others are injured following an attack from suspected Maasai militia at Esoit, Junction and Kirindon in Trans Mara West. Similar violence had occurred in recent weeks.
Residents block roads in protest of pollution of a nearby river.
